-- Targeted migration: fill CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 to spec.
-- 1) Bump questionCount to 90 (official CV0-004 spec: max 90q / 90min).
-- 2) Insert ~195 grounded fill questions across 5 CV0-004 domains
--    (Cloud Architecture, Deployment, Operations, Security, Troubleshooting).
-- Does NOT touch published/deletedAt or title.
-- Idempotent: UPDATE filters; INSERTs guarded by WHERE NOT EXISTS.

CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS pgcrypto;

-- 1) Bump questionCount to 90
UPDATE "Exam" SET "questionCount" = 90
  WHERE code LIKE 'CV0-004-P%' AND "questionCount" <> 90;

-- 2) Insert grounded fill questions
-- CV0-004-P1: 40 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is designing a multi-tier web application that must remain available even if an entire geographic region becomes unavailable. Which architectural pattern BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy all tiers within a single Availability Zone and enable auto-scaling"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a multi-region active-active deployment with global load balancing"},{"id":"c","text":"Replicate data to a secondary region but keep compute resources only in the primary region"},{"id":"d","text":"Use a content delivery network (CDN) as the sole redundancy mechanism"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A multi-region active-active deployment ensures that workloads run simultaneously in two or more geographic regions. If one entire region fails, traffic is automatically routed to the remaining healthy region(s) via a global load balancer, satisfying the regional-failure requirement. Option A fails because a single Availability Zone cannot survive a full region outage. Option C is a warm-standby (active-passive) pattern that still requires failover time and does not keep compute active in the secondary region. Option D (CDN alone) only caches static content at edge nodes; it cannot handle the full application stack during a regional failure.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-fault-isolation-boundaries/regions.html","label":"AWS Multi-Region Architecture Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is designing a multi-tier web application that must remain available even if an entire geographic region becomes unavailable. Which architectural pattern BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization needs to design a cloud solution that can automatically increase compute capacity during business hours and reduce it overnight to minimize costs. Which cloud characteristic BEST enables this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Broad network access"},{"id":"b","text":"Resource pooling"},{"id":"c","text":"Rapid elasticity"},{"id":"d","text":"Measured service"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Rapid elasticity is the NIST-defined cloud characteristic that allows resources to be provisioned and released, automatically or manually, to scale rapidly outward and inward in proportion to demand. Automatically scaling up during business hours and down overnight is a direct application of this characteristic. Broad network access refers to availability over standard networks. Resource pooling refers to the provider serving multiple consumers from shared resources. Measured service refers to metering and billing of resource usage, not the scaling behavior itself.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-145: The NIST Definition of Cloud Computing"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ Certification Page"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization needs to design a cloud solution that can automatically increase compute capacity during business hours and reduce it overnight to minimize costs. Which cloud characteristic BEST enables this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A solutions architect is evaluating deployment models for a healthcare company that must keep patient data on-premises due to regulatory requirements, but also wants to leverage public cloud services for non-sensitive workloads. Which cloud deployment model BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Public cloud only"},{"id":"b","text":"Private cloud only"},{"id":"c","text":"Hybrid cloud"},{"id":"d","text":"Community cloud"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A hybrid cloud deployment combines on-premises private infrastructure with public cloud services, connected by technology that allows data and applications to be shared. This model satisfies the requirement of keeping regulated patient data on-premises while using the public cloud for non-sensitive workloads. A public cloud only model would not allow on-premises data retention. A private cloud only model misses the public cloud cost/scaling benefits. A community cloud is shared among organizations with similar concerns (e.g., healthcare consortiums) but does not inherently solve the on-premises vs. public cloud workload separation requirement.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-145: Cloud Deployment Models"},{"url":"https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/solutions/hybrid-cloud-app/","label":"Microsoft Azure Hybrid Cloud Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A solutions architect is evaluating deployment models for a healthcare company that must keep patient data on-premises due to regulatory requirements, but also wants to leverage public cloud services for non-sensitive workloads. Which cloud deployment model BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$When designing a cloud application, an architect wants to ensure that individual components can be developed, deployed, and scaled independently of one another. Which architectural style BEST supports this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Monolithic architecture"},{"id":"b","text":"Microservices architecture"},{"id":"c","text":"Three-tier architecture"},{"id":"d","text":"Service-oriented architecture (SOA) using a single shared database"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Microservices architecture decomposes an application into small, independently deployable services that each own their own data and can be scaled individually. This directly addresses the requirement for independent development, deployment, and scaling. A monolithic architecture bundles all components together, requiring full redeployment for any change. A three-tier architecture separates presentation, logic, and data, but tiers are typically deployed as units rather than independently scalable micro-components. SOA with a single shared database creates tight coupling at the data layer, preventing true independent scaling and deployment.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/microservices/","label":"AWS Microservices Architecture Overview"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/guide/architecture-styles/microservices","label":"Microsoft Azure Microservices Design Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$When designing a cloud application, an architect wants to ensure that individual components can be developed, deployed, and scaled independently of one another. Which architectural style BEST supports this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is designing a disaster recovery solution and has a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 15 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 5 minutes. Which DR strategy BEST meets both requirements while balancing cost?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Backup and restore, with hourly snapshots sent to cloud object storage"},{"id":"b","text":"Pilot light, with core infrastructure pre-provisioned and data replicated continuously"},{"id":"c","text":"Warm standby, with a scaled-down but fully functional environment receiving near-real-time replication"},{"id":"d","text":"Multi-site active-active, with full capacity running in two regions simultaneously"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A warm standby strategy maintains a scaled-down but fully operational duplicate environment that receives near-real-time data replication, typically meeting an RPO of minutes and an RTO of minutes (including scale-up time). This satisfies the 15-minute RTO and 5-minute RPO targets without the expense of a full active-active setup. Backup and restore typically yields RTOs of hours, violating the 15-minute requirement. A pilot light keeps only the minimal core services running (e.g., a database), requiring more provisioning time on failover, which may risk exceeding a 15-minute RTO. Multi-site active-active meets the targets but is the most expensive option and exceeds what is needed when 'balancing cost' is a factor.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS Disaster Recovery Whitepaper"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/architecture/dr-scenarios-planning-guide","label":"Google Cloud DR Planning Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is designing a disaster recovery solution and has a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 15 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 5 minutes. Which DR strategy BEST meets both requirements while balancing cost?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An architect is designing a cloud storage solution for an application that generates millions of small files per day. The files must be stored durably and accessed infrequently after 30 days. Which storage tier selection approach BEST optimizes cost and durability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store all objects in a high-performance block storage volume"},{"id":"b","text":"Store all objects in a standard object storage class and never transition them"},{"id":"c","text":"Use lifecycle policies to automatically transition objects to an infrequent-access object storage tier after 30 days"},{"id":"d","text":"Archive all objects immediately upon creation to the lowest-cost cold storage tier"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Object storage lifecycle policies automatically move objects between storage tiers based on age or access patterns. Transitioning to an infrequent-access tier after 30 days maintains high durability (typically 11 nines) while significantly reducing storage costs for objects that are no longer accessed frequently. Block storage is optimized for low-latency transactional I/O, not for storing millions of small files cost-effectively. Keeping all objects in the standard tier indefinitely is the most expensive option. Archiving immediately upon creation would incur retrieval delays and fees for any objects needed within the first 30 days.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/lifecycle-transition-general-considerations.html","label":"AWS S3 Storage Classes and Lifecycle Policies"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/lifecycle","label":"Google Cloud Storage Object Lifecycle Management"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An architect is designing a cloud storage solution for an application that generates millions of small files per day. The files must be stored durably and accessed infrequently after 30 days. Which storage tier selection approach BEST optimizes cost and durability?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect must design a network topology that allows multiple VPCs (Virtual Private Clouds) within the same cloud provider account to communicate privately without traversing the public internet, while minimizing the number of peering connections needed as more VPCs are added. Which network architecture BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a full-mesh VPC peering between all VPCs"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a transit gateway (or hub VPC) to centralize connectivity between all VPCs"},{"id":"c","text":"Assign public Elastic IPs to instances in each VPC and use TLS for communication"},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy a VPN tunnel between each pair of VPCs"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A transit gateway (or hub-and-spoke architecture with a central hub VPC) connects all VPCs through a single central point. Adding a new VPC requires only one new connection to the transit gateway, making the topology scale linearly (O(n)) rather than quadratically. Full-mesh VPC peering requires n*(n-1)/2 connections, which becomes operationally complex and costly as VPC count grows, and VPC peering is also non-transitive. Using public Elastic IPs exposes traffic to the internet, violating the private communication requirement. VPN tunnels between each pair suffer the same quadratic scaling problem as full-mesh peering, with additional overhead.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/tgw/what-is-transit-gateway.html","label":"AWS Transit Gateway Documentation"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-wan/virtual-wan-about","label":"Azure Virtual WAN (Hub-and-Spoke) Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect must design a network topology that allows multiple VPCs (Virtual Private Clouds) within the same cloud provider account to communicate privately without traversing the public internet, while minimizing the number of peering connections needed as more VPCs are added. Which network architecture BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company plans to adopt a cloud service model where the provider manages the underlying infrastructure, operating system, middleware, and runtime, while the company is responsible only for deploying and managing its own application code and data. Which service model describes this arrangement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)"},{"id":"b","text":"Platform as a Service (PaaS)"},{"id":"c","text":"Software as a Service (SaaS)"},{"id":"d","text":"Function as a Service (FaaS)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Platform as a Service (PaaS) abstracts the infrastructure, OS, middleware, and runtime from the customer. The customer is responsible only for the application code and data, which matches the scenario exactly. IaaS provides virtualized compute, storage, and networking, but the customer must still manage the OS and above. SaaS delivers a complete, ready-to-use application managed entirely by the provider, leaving the customer responsible only for their use of the application (not code deployment). FaaS (serverless functions) is a subset of PaaS focused on individual functions triggered by events; the customer deploys function code but has no control over the broader application platform.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-145: Cloud Service Models"},{"url":"https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/resources/cloud-computing-dictionary/what-are-private-public-hybrid-clouds/","label":"Microsoft Azure IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company plans to adopt a cloud service model where the provider manages the underlying infrastructure, operating system, middleware, and runtime, while the company is responsible only for deploying and managing its own application code and data. Which service model describes this arrangement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During the design phase of a new cloud application, an architect is documenting all resources and their interactions using standardized notation. The architect needs to visually represent the flow of data between a user's browser, an API gateway, a compute cluster, and a managed database. Which artifact is MOST appropriate for this purpose?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A Gantt chart"},{"id":"b","text":"A data flow diagram (DFD)"},{"id":"c","text":"A risk register"},{"id":"d","text":"A cost estimation spreadsheet"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A data flow diagram (DFD) is specifically designed to illustrate how data moves between processes, data stores, and external entities within a system. It is the standard artifact for depicting the flow of data from a user browser through an API gateway, compute cluster, and database. A Gantt chart is a project scheduling tool showing tasks over time, not data flows. A risk register catalogs identified risks and their mitigations. A cost estimation spreadsheet tracks projected cloud spending. None of these three are suitable for visualizing component interactions and data movement.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-160v1r1.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-160 Vol. 1: Systems Security Engineering"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/certmaster-learn/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ Study Guide (CertMaster)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During the design phase of a new cloud application, an architect is documenting all resources and their interactions using standardized notation. The architect needs to visually represent the flow of data between a user's browser, an API gateway, a compute cluster, and a managed database. Which artifact is MOST appropriate for this purpose?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to design a cloud environment where every resource is treated as potentially compromised and all access requests—regardless of network location—must be continuously verified. Which security model BEST aligns with this design principle?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Perimeter-based security (castle-and-moat)"},{"id":"b","text":"Zero Trust Architecture"},{"id":"c","text":"Defense in depth with a single DMZ"},{"id":"d","text":"Air-gapped network isolation"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) is built on the principle of 'never trust, always verify.' It assumes breach and requires continuous authentication and authorization of all requests regardless of whether they originate inside or outside the network perimeter. This directly matches the described design goal. Perimeter-based (castle-and-moat) security trusts everything inside the network perimeter, which is the antithesis of the requirement. Defense in depth with a single DMZ still relies on a trusted interior zone. Air-gapped isolation physically separates networks but does not provide continuous per-request verification for users and services already inside the environment.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-207.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-207: Zero Trust Architecture"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/security/zero-trust/zero-trust-overview","label":"Microsoft Zero Trust Guidance Center"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to design a cloud environment where every resource is treated as potentially compromised and all access requests—regardless of network location—must be continuously verified. Which security model BEST aligns with this design principle?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is designing an application that must process a high volume of orders. The order submission service and the fulfillment service must be decoupled so that a spike in orders does not cause the fulfillment service to fail. Which design pattern BEST achieves this decoupling?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Synchronous REST API calls from the order service directly to the fulfillment service"},{"id":"b","text":"A shared relational database table that both services poll simultaneously"},{"id":"c","text":"A message queue between the order service (producer) and the fulfillment service (consumer)"},{"id":"d","text":"A direct gRPC streaming connection between the two services"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A message queue implements the producer-consumer pattern, which decouples the rate at which messages are produced from the rate at which they are consumed. During a spike, orders accumulate in the queue and the fulfillment service processes them at its own pace, preventing overload. Synchronous REST calls create tight temporal coupling: if the fulfillment service is slow or down, the order service is also affected. A shared polling table introduces contention, locking issues, and is not a best-practice messaging pattern. A direct gRPC streaming connection is still a synchronous, tightly coupled channel—if the fulfillment service is overwhelmed, back-pressure propagates to the order service.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/welcome.html","label":"AWS SQS (Simple Queue Service) Developer Guide"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/service-bus-messaging/service-bus-queues-topics-subscriptions","label":"Azure Service Bus Queues, Topics, and Subscriptions"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is designing an application that must process a high volume of orders. The order submission service and the fulfillment service must be decoupled so that a spike in orders does not cause the fulfillment service to fail. Which design pattern BEST achieves this decoupling?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a three-tier web application on a public cloud provider. The deployment requires that the database tier is never directly accessible from the internet. Which network architecture component BEST enforces this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Place the database tier in a private subnet with no internet gateway route"},{"id":"b","text":"Attach a public IP address to the database instances and restrict inbound traffic using a security group"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable DDoS protection on the database subnet"},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy the database tier in a separate availability zone from the web tier"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Placing the database tier in a private subnet that has no route to an internet gateway ensures the instances are unreachable from the public internet at the network layer. A public IP with security-group restrictions (option B) still exposes the instance to the internet and relies solely on rule configuration. DDoS protection (option C) mitigates volumetric attacks but does not prevent internet accessibility. Separate availability zones (option D) address fault tolerance, not internet exposure.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/configure-subnets.html","label":"AWS VPC Subnets – Private vs Public"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a three-tier web application on a public cloud provider. The deployment requires that the database tier is never directly accessible from the internet. Which network architecture component BEST enforces this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud deployment, a DevOps team wants to ensure that infrastructure changes are version-controlled, repeatable, and auditable. Which practice BEST satisfies all three requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Manually applying changes through the cloud provider console and logging screenshots"},{"id":"b","text":"Storing infrastructure definitions as code in a source-control repository and deploying through a CI/CD pipeline"},{"id":"c","text":"Using the cloud provider CLI in ad-hoc scripts saved on individual engineers' workstations"},{"id":"d","text":"Documenting changes in a spreadsheet after each deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) stored in a source-control repository provides version history, peer review via pull requests, and reproducible deployments through a CI/CD pipeline—satisfying all three requirements. Manual console changes (option A) are error-prone and not inherently version-controlled. Ad-hoc CLI scripts (option C) are not centrally versioned or auditable. Spreadsheet documentation (option D) is reactive and not enforceable.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ Study Guide – Infrastructure as Code"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/tutorials/aws-get-started/infrastructure-as-code","label":"HashiCorp – What is Infrastructure as Code?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud deployment, a DevOps team wants to ensure that infrastructure changes are version-controlled, repeatable, and auditable. Which practice BEST satisfies all three requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is deploying a containerized microservices application on Kubernetes. They need to ensure that a minimum of three replicas of a critical service are always running. Which Kubernetes object enforces this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"DaemonSet"},{"id":"b","text":"StatefulSet"},{"id":"c","text":"Deployment with a replica count of 3"},{"id":"d","text":"CronJob"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Kubernetes Deployment object allows you to declare a desired replica count; the ReplicaSet controller continuously reconciles the actual state to match, ensuring at least three pods are running. A DaemonSet (option A) runs one pod per node, not a fixed replica count. A StatefulSet (option B) is used for stateful applications requiring stable identities, not simply for enforcing replica counts of stateless services. A CronJob (option D) schedules batch jobs on a time basis and is unrelated to keeping a minimum number of long-running replicas.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/","label":"Kubernetes Deployments"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is deploying a containerized microservices application on Kubernetes. They need to ensure that a minimum of three replicas of a critical service are always running. Which Kubernetes object enforces this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization is migrating an on-premises application to the cloud and must choose a deployment model that allows them to shift workloads between their private data center and the public cloud based on demand. Which cloud deployment model BEST meets this need?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Public cloud"},{"id":"b","text":"Private cloud"},{"id":"c","text":"Hybrid cloud"},{"id":"d","text":"Community cloud"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A hybrid cloud model connects a private data center with a public cloud, enabling workload portability and demand-based bursting (cloud bursting). A pure public cloud (option A) does not include the private data center component. A private cloud (option B) lacks the public cloud elasticity. A community cloud (option D) is shared among organizations with similar needs but does not provide the on-premises-to-public elasticity described.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST Definition of Cloud Computing (SP 800-145)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization is migrating an on-premises application to the cloud and must choose a deployment model that allows them to shift workloads between their private data center and the public cloud based on demand. Which cloud deployment model BEST meets this need?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect needs to deploy an application update with zero downtime. The new version must be validated in production with real traffic before fully replacing the old version. Which deployment strategy BEST fulfills this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Recreate deployment"},{"id":"b","text":"Canary deployment"},{"id":"c","text":"Blue/green deployment"},{"id":"d","text":"Rolling deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A canary deployment routes a small percentage of live traffic to the new version while the majority continues to the stable version, allowing real-world validation before a full rollout. A recreate deployment (option A) terminates all old instances before starting new ones, causing downtime. Blue/green deployment (option C) switches all traffic at once to the new environment; it provides zero downtime but does not incrementally validate with a subset of real traffic. A rolling deployment (option D) gradually replaces instances but does not easily allow splitting a defined percentage of traffic for validation.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/architecture/application-deployment-and-testing-strategies","label":"Google Cloud – Deployment Strategies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect needs to deploy an application update with zero downtime. The new version must be validated in production with real traffic before fully replacing the old version. Which deployment strategy BEST fulfills this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A team is using a CI/CD pipeline to deploy application code to a cloud environment. After a new build passes all automated tests, the pipeline automatically promotes the artifact to the production environment without any manual approval step. This practice is BEST described as which of the following?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Continuous integration"},{"id":"b","text":"Continuous delivery"},{"id":"c","text":"Continuous deployment"},{"id":"d","text":"Continuous monitoring"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Continuous deployment (CD) means every change that passes automated tests is automatically released to production with no manual intervention. Continuous integration (option A) focuses on automatically building and testing code commits but does not release to production. Continuous delivery (option B) also automates up to a production-ready state but requires a manual approval gate before the final push to production. Continuous monitoring (option D) refers to ongoing observation of systems, not release automation.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.atlassian.com/continuous-delivery/principles/continuous-integration-vs-delivery-vs-deployment","label":"Atlassian – Continuous Integration vs. Delivery vs. Deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A team is using a CI/CD pipeline to deploy application code to a cloud environment. After a new build passes all automated tests, the pipeline automatically promotes the artifact to the production environment without any manual approval step. This practice is BEST described as which of the following?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is deploying virtual machines using an infrastructure-as-code template. The template must reference a secret database password without embedding the plaintext credential in the template file. Which solution BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Hard-code the password directly in the IaC template and restrict repository access"},{"id":"b","text":"Store the password in a cloud secrets manager and reference it by ARN or resource ID in the template"},{"id":"c","text":"Base64-encode the password and embed it in the template"},{"id":"d","text":"Pass the password as a plain-text environment variable in the CI/CD pipeline log"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cloud secrets managers (e.g., AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault) store credentials securely and allow IaC templates to retrieve them at deployment time using a reference, keeping plaintext out of the template and version history. Hard-coding (option A) exposes the secret in source control regardless of access restrictions. Base64 encoding (option C) is not encryption and is trivially reversible. Logging the password as a plain-text environment variable (option D) exposes it in pipeline logs, which is a significant security risk.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/integrating_cloudformation.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Use Secrets in AWS CloudFormation"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-resource-manager/templates/key-vault-parameter","label":"Azure Key Vault with ARM Templates"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is deploying virtual machines using an infrastructure-as-code template. The template must reference a secret database password without embedding the plaintext credential in the template file. Which solution BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud deployment team is about to release a major application update. To minimize risk, they provision an identical production environment running the new version, then instantly redirect all user traffic to it. If issues arise, they switch traffic back to the original environment. Which deployment strategy does this describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Canary deployment"},{"id":"b","text":"A/B testing deployment"},{"id":"c","text":"Blue/green deployment"},{"id":"d","text":"Shadow deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Blue/green deployment maintains two identical environments (blue = current, green = new). Traffic is cut over all at once to the green environment, and rollback is achieved by redirecting traffic back to blue. A canary deployment (option A) routes only a percentage of traffic to the new version incrementally. A/B testing (option B) routes traffic to different versions to compare feature performance, not primarily for safe release. Shadow deployment (option D) mirrors live traffic to a new version without serving responses to users, used for testing only.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/blue-green-deployments/blue-green-deployments.pdf","label":"AWS – Blue/Green Deployments on AWS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud deployment team is about to release a major application update. To minimize risk, they provision an identical production environment running the new version, then instantly redirect all user traffic to it. If issues arise, they switch traffic back to the original environment. Which deployment strategy does this describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to deploy a stateless web application that must scale automatically based on HTTP request volume and requires no server management. Which cloud service model is MOST appropriate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) with manually configured auto-scaling groups"},{"id":"b","text":"Platform as a Service (PaaS) or serverless function platform"},{"id":"c","text":"Software as a Service (SaaS)"},{"id":"d","text":"Bare-metal dedicated servers"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$PaaS and serverless (FaaS) platforms abstract server management entirely and scale automatically based on incoming request volume, satisfying both requirements. IaaS with auto-scaling groups (option A) still requires the team to manage OS, patching, and scaling configuration. SaaS (option C) is a fully managed application delivered to end users, not a deployment model for custom application code. Bare-metal (option D) requires full physical server management and offers no automatic scaling.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST Cloud Service Models (SP 800-145)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/welcome.html","label":"AWS Lambda – Serverless Computing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to deploy a stateless web application that must scale automatically based on HTTP request volume and requires no server management. Which cloud service model is MOST appropriate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is deploying a new microservice using a container image stored in a private registry. The Kubernetes cluster must authenticate to the registry to pull the image. Which Kubernetes object is used to store the registry credentials securely?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"ConfigMap"},{"id":"b","text":"ServiceAccount"},{"id":"c","text":"Secret of type kubernetes.io/dockerconfigjson"},{"id":"d","text":"PersistentVolumeClaim"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A Kubernetes Secret of type kubernetes.io/dockerconfigjson stores Docker registry authentication credentials and can be referenced as an imagePullSecret in a Pod or Deployment spec. A ConfigMap (option A) stores non-sensitive configuration data in plain text and is not appropriate for credentials. A ServiceAccount (option B) grants API permissions to pods within the cluster but does not itself store registry credentials. A PersistentVolumeClaim (option D) is used to request storage resources, not authentication data.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/configure-pod-container/pull-image-private-registry/","label":"Kubernetes – Pull an Image from a Private Registry"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is deploying a new microservice using a container image stored in a private registry. The Kubernetes cluster must authenticate to the registry to pull the image. Which Kubernetes object is used to store the registry credentials securely?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud deployment, an engineer needs to validate that a new IaC template will not cause unintended resource deletions before applying it to production. Which action should the engineer take FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply the template directly to the production environment and monitor for errors"},{"id":"b","text":"Run a dry-run or plan operation (e.g., terraform plan) to preview the changes before applying"},{"id":"c","text":"Delete all existing resources and redeploy from scratch"},{"id":"d","text":"Disable all monitoring alerts to prevent noise during deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Running a plan/dry-run command (such as 'terraform plan' in Terraform or 'aws cloudformation change-set' in CloudFormation) shows a detailed diff of what will be created, modified, or destroyed without making any actual changes. This allows the engineer to catch unintended deletions before they impact production. Applying directly to production (option A) risks unintended outages. Deleting and redeploying (option C) causes unnecessary downtime. Disabling monitoring (option D) is a dangerous anti-pattern that removes visibility during a critical operation.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform – The Plan Command"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-updating-stacks-changesets.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation Change Sets"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud deployment, an engineer needs to validate that a new IaC template will not cause unintended resource deletions before applying it to production. Which action should the engineer take FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations team must deploy the same application stack across development, staging, and production environments, ensuring configuration differences (e.g., instance sizes, connection strings) are managed without duplicating template code. Which IaC approach BEST supports this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Maintain three completely separate, manually edited templates for each environment"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a single parameterized template with environment-specific variable files (e.g., tfvars or parameter files)"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy all environments using the exact same configuration with no differentiation"},{"id":"d","text":"Configure each environment manually through the cloud provider console after initial deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A parameterized IaC template uses variables to externalize environment-specific values; separate variable files (e.g., dev.tfvars, prod.tfvars) supply the correct values per environment without duplicating core template logic. Maintaining separate full templates (option A) introduces drift and maintenance overhead. Using identical configurations (option C) ignores real-world differences in sizing and connections that exist between environments. Manual console configuration (option D) reintroduces undocumented, non-repeatable changes after the initial deploy.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/values/variables","label":"Terraform – Input Variables and .tfvars Files"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-resource-manager/bicep/parameters","label":"Azure Bicep – Parameters"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations team must deploy the same application stack across development, staging, and production environments, ensuring configuration differences (e.g., instance sizes, connection strings) are managed without duplicating template code. Which IaC approach BEST supports this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An application deployment requires that new container instances pass a health check before receiving production traffic, and that unhealthy instances are automatically removed from the load balancer. Which mechanism enforces this behavior in a Kubernetes environment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Resource quotas"},{"id":"b","text":"Liveness and readiness probes"},{"id":"c","text":"Horizontal Pod Autoscaler"},{"id":"d","text":"Network policies"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Kubernetes readiness probes determine when a pod is ready to accept traffic; until the probe succeeds, the pod is removed from the Service endpoints (load balancer pool). Liveness probes detect when a running container has become unhealthy and trigger a restart. Resource quotas (option A) limit resource consumption, not traffic routing. Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (option C) scales pod counts based on metrics but does not manage traffic routing for unhealthy pods. Network policies (option D) control traffic flow between pods at the network layer, not health-based traffic management.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/configure-pod-container/configure-liveness-readiness-startup-probes/","label":"Kubernetes – Configure Liveness, Readiness and Startup Probes"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An application deployment requires that new container instances pass a health check before receiving production traffic, and that unhealthy instances are automatically removed from the load balancer. Which mechanism enforces this behavior in a Kubernetes environment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is packaging an application for cloud deployment and wants to ensure it runs consistently across different environments by bundling the application code, runtime, libraries, and configuration together. Which technology BEST achieves this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Virtual machine snapshot"},{"id":"b","text":"Container image"},{"id":"c","text":"SSH configuration file"},{"id":"d","text":"Object storage bucket"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A container image packages application code, runtime, libraries, and configuration into a single, immutable, portable artifact that runs consistently regardless of the underlying host environment. VM snapshots (option A) capture the entire OS state of a virtual machine and are heavyweight, environment-specific, and not designed for application portability across different cloud environments. An SSH configuration file (option C) is used for remote access, not application packaging. Object storage (option D) stores unstructured data but does not provide a runtime environment.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.docker.com/resources/what-container/","label":"Docker – What is a Container?"},{"url":"https://github.com/opencontainers/image-spec/blob/main/spec.md","label":"OCI Image Format Specification"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is packaging an application for cloud deployment and wants to ensure it runs consistently across different environments by bundling the application code, runtime, libraries, and configuration together. Which technology BEST achieves this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud deployment pipeline, an automated security scanning step discovers a critical vulnerability in a third-party library used by the application image. According to deployment best practices, what should the pipeline do NEXT?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Continue the deployment and log the vulnerability for remediation in the next sprint"},{"id":"b","text":"Fail the pipeline build, notify the development team, and block promotion to higher environments until the vulnerability is remediated"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy to production immediately to minimize the window of exposure"},{"id":"d","text":"Remove the security scanning step to allow the pipeline to proceed"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Security scanning integrated into CI/CD pipelines (a 'shift-left' security practice) should fail the build on critical findings to enforce a policy gate, preventing vulnerable code from progressing to higher environments. Continuing the deployment (option A) knowingly ships a critical vulnerability. Deploying immediately (option C) is counterproductive and introduces a known critical risk into production. Removing the scan step (option D) eliminates a vital security control and violates secure DevOps principles.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://owasp.org/www-project-devsecops-guideline/","label":"OWASP DevSecOps Guideline"},{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-190.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-190 – Application Container Security Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud deployment pipeline, an automated security scanning step discovers a critical vulnerability in a third-party library used by the application image. According to deployment best practices, what should the pipeline do NEXT?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying resources using Terraform and needs to store the Terraform state file so that multiple team members can collaborate without overwriting each other's changes. Which storage approach is considered BEST practice for team-based IaC workflows?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Each engineer maintains a local copy of the state file on their workstation"},{"id":"b","text":"Commit the state file to the application's Git repository"},{"id":"c","text":"Store the state file in a remote backend (e.g., cloud object storage with state locking enabled)"},{"id":"d","text":"Regenerate the state file from scratch before every deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A remote backend such as an S3 bucket with DynamoDB locking (AWS), Azure Blob Storage, or Terraform Cloud stores the state file in a shared, durable location and enables state locking to prevent concurrent modifications that can corrupt state. Local copies (option A) cause state divergence across team members. Committing state to Git (option B) risks exposing sensitive resource details and causes merge conflicts. Regenerating state (option D) is not feasible because Terraform state tracks real infrastructure; regenerating it would cause Terraform to lose track of existing resources.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/state/remote","label":"Terraform – Remote State"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/backend/s3","label":"Terraform – S3 Backend Configuration"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying resources using Terraform and needs to store the Terraform state file so that multiple team members can collaborate without overwriting each other's changes. Which storage approach is considered BEST practice for team-based IaC workflows?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations engineer needs to ensure that a production workload running on a public cloud IaaS platform meets its defined Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 30 minutes. Which operational strategy BEST supports achieving this RTO in the event of a regional cloud provider outage?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure daily snapshots of all virtual machine disks stored in the same region"},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy a warm standby environment in a secondary region with automated failover via a load balancer health check"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable object versioning on the primary storage bucket to allow point-in-time recovery"},{"id":"d","text":"Implement a cold standby in a secondary region and restore from the most recent nightly backup"},{"id":"e","text":"Increase the instance size of the primary workload to reduce the likelihood of failure"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A warm standby in a secondary region keeps a scaled-down but fully functional copy of the production environment running at all times. Automated failover via health checks allows traffic to shift to the secondary region quickly, making a 30-minute RTO achievable. Option A stores snapshots in the same region, providing no protection against a regional outage. Option C (object versioning) addresses data recovery, not compute availability. Option D (cold standby) requires provisioning and restoring from backup, which typically exceeds a 30-minute RTO. Option E (upsizing the primary instance) improves performance, not regional resilience.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/warm-standby.html","label":"AWS Disaster Recovery Workloads on AWS – Warm Standby"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations engineer needs to ensure that a production workload running on a public cloud IaaS platform meets its defined Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 30 minutes. Which operational strategy BEST supports achieving this RTO in the event of a regional cloud provider outage?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team is reviewing cloud resource utilization reports and notices that several virtual machine instances consistently operate at less than 10% CPU utilization over a 30-day period. Which action BEST optimizes cost while maintaining operational capability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Terminate all underutilized instances immediately to reduce spend"},{"id":"b","text":"Right-size the instances to a smaller SKU that matches the observed workload profile"},{"id":"c","text":"Move the instances to a different availability zone to balance resource usage"},{"id":"d","text":"Increase monitoring frequency to collect more granular utilization data"},{"id":"e","text":"Convert the instances to reserved instances at their current size without any changes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Right-sizing adjusts the compute instance type or SKU to match the actual workload demand, directly reducing cost while keeping the workloads operational. Option A (immediate termination) may disrupt valid workloads that have low average CPU but still serve a purpose. Option C (changing availability zones) does not reduce cost and does not address the utilization issue. Option D (increasing monitoring frequency) improves data granularity but alone does not reduce cost. Option E (converting to reserved instances at the same size) locks in cost commitments for an over-provisioned size, missing the opportunity to reduce per-unit cost through right-sizing first.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/resize-vm","label":"Microsoft Azure – Resize a virtual machine"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cost-management/latest/userguide/ce-rightsizing.html","label":"AWS Cost Optimization – Right Sizing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team is reviewing cloud resource utilization reports and notices that several virtual machine instances consistently operate at less than 10% CPU utilization over a 30-day period. Which action BEST optimizes cost while maintaining operational capability?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator is implementing a patch management process for a fleet of Linux virtual machines hosted in a public cloud. The organization requires that patches be tested before being applied to production. Which workflow BEST represents a structured and safe patch management lifecycle?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply patches directly to production instances during a maintenance window, then roll back if issues arise"},{"id":"b","text":"Subscribe all production instances to the vendor's automatic update channel to receive patches immediately upon release"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy patches to a staging environment first, validate functionality, then promote tested patches to production during a change window"},{"id":"d","text":"Scan production instances for vulnerabilities monthly and apply all critical patches quarterly"},{"id":"e","text":"Disable automatic updates and rely on immutable infrastructure to avoid the need for patching"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A staging-then-production pipeline is the industry-standard patch lifecycle: patches are applied in a non-production environment, validated against application functionality and stability, and only then promoted to production during an approved change window. This minimizes risk and supports change management governance. Option A applies patches directly to production, which risks service disruption without a validation gate. Option B (auto-updates in production) bypasses testing and can break production workloads. Option D (quarterly critical patches) leaves systems exposed for too long, violating most security baselines. Option E misapplies the concept of immutable infrastructure; even immutable environments require updated base images, and disabling updates entirely creates unacceptable risk.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-40r4.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-40 Rev. 4 – Guide to Enterprise Patch Management Planning"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-patch.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator is implementing a patch management process for a fleet of Linux virtual machines hosted in a public cloud. The organization requires that patches be tested before being applied to production. Which workflow BEST represents a structured and safe patch management lifecycle?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's cloud monitoring system generates hundreds of alerts per day, many of which are noise and do not require human action. The operations team wants to reduce mean time to respond (MTTR) to genuine incidents. Which approach BEST addresses alert fatigue while preserving visibility into real issues?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase alert thresholds globally so that fewer alerts are generated across all services"},{"id":"b","text":"Disable alerting for non-critical services and only monitor Tier-1 workloads"},{"id":"c","text":"Implement alert correlation and automatic suppression of known transient conditions, and use severity-based routing to the appropriate on-call team"},{"id":"d","text":"Require all alerts to go through a ticketing system and have engineers triage them at the start of each business day"},{"id":"e","text":"Replace all threshold-based alerts with scheduled daily health-check reports"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Alert correlation groups related alerts into a single incident record, reducing noise, while automatic suppression of known transient conditions (e.g., brief network blips during deployments) prevents false positives. Severity-based routing ensures that critical alerts reach the right on-call team immediately, directly reducing MTTR. Option A (raising thresholds globally) risks masking real problems. Option B (disabling non-critical alerts) creates blind spots. Option D (daily triage) introduces unnecessary delay for time-sensitive incidents. Option E (daily health reports) replaces real-time alerting with periodic reports, which is unsuitable for dynamic cloud environments where issues can emerge and escalate rapidly.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/monitoring/alerts/concepts-indepth","label":"Google Cloud – Best practices for monitoring and alerting"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/alerts/alerts-processing-rules","label":"Microsoft Azure Monitor – Alert processing rules"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's cloud monitoring system generates hundreds of alerts per day, many of which are noise and do not require human action. The operations team wants to reduce mean time to respond (MTTR) to genuine incidents. Which approach BEST addresses alert fatigue while preserving visibility into real issues?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization uses a cloud-based infrastructure-as-code (IaC) pipeline to manage its environment. After a recent deployment, a misconfigured security group inadvertently exposed a database port to the public internet. The team wants to prevent similar configuration drift in the future. Which operational control BEST prevents this type of drift from reaching production?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Schedule a weekly manual review of all security group rules by the cloud administrator"},{"id":"b","text":"Integrate a policy-as-code compliance check into the CI/CD pipeline that blocks deployments violating defined security baselines"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable cloud provider audit logging and review the logs monthly for unauthorized changes"},{"id":"d","text":"Tag all cloud resources with an owner label so that misconfigured resources can be identified quickly"},{"id":"e","text":"Require all IaC changes to be submitted via a help-desk ticket for manual approval before execution"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Integrating policy-as-code (e.g., Open Policy Agent, AWS CloudFormation Guard, or Azure Policy) directly into the CI/CD pipeline provides automated, consistent enforcement of security baselines before changes are deployed. This is a preventive control that stops non-compliant configurations from ever reaching production. Option A (weekly manual review) is a detective control that is too slow and error-prone to catch all drift before it causes harm. Option C (monthly log review) is also detective and reactive, not preventive. Option D (resource tagging) aids identification and attribution but does not prevent misconfiguration. Option E (help-desk tickets) introduces manual latency and human error into what should be an automated enforcement gate, reducing pipeline velocity without guaranteeing accuracy.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cfn-guard/latest/ug/what-is-guard.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation Guard – Policy-as-code for IaC"},{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/sentinel/docs/intro/what","label":"HashiCorp Sentinel – Policy as Code Framework"},{"url":"https://www.openpolicyagent.org/docs/latest/","label":"Open Policy Agent Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization uses a cloud-based infrastructure-as-code (IaC) pipeline to manage its environment. After a recent deployment, a misconfigured security group inadvertently exposed a database port to the public internet. The team wants to prevent similar configuration drift in the future. Which operational control BEST prevents this type of drift from reaching production?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator receives alerts that a production web application hosted on a virtual machine is intermittently returning HTTP 504 Gateway Timeout errors to end users. The VM appears healthy and CPU/memory utilization is within normal ranges. Which step should the administrator take FIRST to isolate the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Reboot the virtual machine to clear any transient network state."},{"id":"b","text":"Review the load balancer access logs and health-check configuration to determine whether back-end targets are being marked unhealthy."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the VM instance size to add more CPU and RAM resources."},{"id":"d","text":"Redeploy the application from the last known-good snapshot."},{"id":"e","text":"Disable auto-scaling to prevent additional instances from being launched during the investigation."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An HTTP 504 Gateway Timeout indicates that an upstream or back-end component is not responding in time, not that the origin VM itself is down. Because CPU/memory metrics are normal, the most logical first step is to inspect the load balancer—its access logs will show which targets are failing health checks and how long requests are taking before timing out. This approach follows the systematic troubleshooting principle of examining the component closest to the reported error before making changes. Rebooting the VM (a) could introduce unnecessary downtime and does not confirm a root cause. Upsizing the VM (c) is premature without evidence of resource exhaustion. Redeploying from a snapshot (d) risks data loss and does not diagnose the issue. Disabling auto-scaling (e) could worsen availability and is unrelated to a timeout problem.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-troubleshooting.html","label":"AWS Elastic Load Balancing – Troubleshooting"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator receives alerts that a production web application hosted on a virtual machine is intermittently returning HTTP 504 Gateway Timeout errors to end users. The VM appears healthy and CPU/memory utilization is within normal ranges. Which step should the administrator take FIRST to isolate the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a routine maintenance window, users report they can no longer reach a cloud-hosted application using its public DNS hostname, although the underlying virtual machine is running and pingable by IP address from within the VPC. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The virtual machine's operating system firewall is blocking inbound traffic."},{"id":"b","text":"The DNS A record was not updated or was accidentally deleted during the maintenance window."},{"id":"c","text":"The cloud provider's backbone network is experiencing a regional outage."},{"id":"d","text":"The TLS certificate on the application server has expired."},{"id":"e","text":"The VM's elastic/public IP address was reassigned to a different resource."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["e"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Because the VM is reachable by its private IP from within the VPC but not by its public DNS hostname, the most probable cause is that the elastic or public IP that the DNS record points to was disassociated or reassigned during maintenance, leaving the DNS record pointing to an IP that no longer belongs to this VM. The DNS record itself (b) could also be a culprit, but if the record still exists and resolves, it would point to the reassigned IP—making IP disassociation the more precise root cause when the VM is healthy inside the VPC. An OS firewall (a) would block traffic at both the IP and DNS level equally. A regional outage (c) would affect more than one resource. An expired TLS certificate (d) would produce a browser security warning, not a connectivity failure. Always verify elastic IP associations immediately after maintenance that involves stop/start cycles, because some cloud providers release elastic IPs when a VM is stopped.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/elastic-ip-addresses-eip.html","label":"AWS – Elastic IP Addresses"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/ip-services/public-ip-addresses","label":"Azure Public IP Addresses Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a routine maintenance window, users report they can no longer reach a cloud-hosted application using its public DNS hostname, although the underlying virtual machine is running and pingable by IP address from within the VPC. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team reports that an auto-scaling group is continuously launching and terminating instances every few minutes, causing application instability. CloudWatch metrics show CPU utilization oscillating between 48% and 55%. Which configuration change would BEST resolve this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the maximum instance count in the auto-scaling group."},{"id":"b","text":"Adjust the scale-in and scale-out cooldown periods and widen the threshold band between scale-out and scale-in triggers."},{"id":"c","text":"Switch the scaling metric from CPU utilization to network throughput."},{"id":"d","text":"Disable scale-in actions so instances are never terminated automatically."},{"id":"e","text":"Replace the auto-scaling group with a fixed, manually managed set of instances."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The described behavior is called 'scaling thrash' or 'flapping,' which occurs when scale-out and scale-in thresholds are too close together and cooldown periods are too short. When a new instance launches, CPU drops slightly below the scale-in threshold, triggering termination, which raises CPU again and triggers another scale-out. Widening the threshold band (e.g., scale out at 70%, scale in at 30%) and extending cooldown periods gives the fleet time to stabilize before another scaling action is evaluated. Increasing the maximum count (a) does not fix the oscillation. Changing the metric (c) may help in some cases but does not address the fundamental threshold/cooldown misconfiguration. Disabling scale-in (d) prevents termination but leads to over-provisioning and cost waste. Removing auto-scaling entirely (e) eliminates elasticity, which is a core cloud benefit.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-scaling-cooldowns.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling – Scaling Cooldowns"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/autoscale/autoscale-best-practices","label":"Azure VMSS Autoscale Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team reports that an auto-scaling group is continuously launching and terminating instances every few minutes, causing application instability. CloudWatch metrics show CPU utilization oscillating between 48% and 55%. Which configuration change would BEST resolve this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer notices that a newly deployed containerized microservice cannot communicate with a backend database VM in the same cloud VPC. Both resources are in the same region. The database VM accepts connections from other VMs on port 5432. Which of the following should the engineer check FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the container image was built from an approved base image."},{"id":"b","text":"The security group or network ACL rules applied to the database VM to confirm they permit inbound traffic from the container subnet or IP range on port 5432."},{"id":"c","text":"The container orchestrator node pool version to ensure it is up to date."},{"id":"d","text":"Whether a service mesh is installed in the cluster."},{"id":"e","text":"The database transaction log for deadlock events."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When a newly introduced workload cannot reach an existing resource on a specific port, the first troubleshooting step is to verify network-layer access controls—security groups and/or network ACLs—because these are the most common reason a new source IP or subnet is blocked. Container workloads typically run in a different IP range than traditional VMs, so the existing security group rule that allows other VMs may not cover the container CIDR. The base image (a) affects security posture but not TCP connectivity. The node pool version (c) is a management concern unrelated to port-level connectivity. A service mesh (d) controls east-west traffic within the cluster, not external database connectivity. Transaction log deadlocks (e) would only be relevant if connectivity was established but queries were hanging.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/ec2-security-groups.html","label":"AWS Security Groups for EC2"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/network-security-groups-overview","label":"Azure Network Security Groups Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer notices that a newly deployed containerized microservice cannot communicate with a backend database VM in the same cloud VPC. Both resources are in the same region. The database VM accepts connections from other VMs on port 5432. Which of the following should the engineer check FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Users report that application response times have degraded significantly over the past 24 hours. A cloud administrator checks the managed relational database and finds that storage I/O latency has increased from 2 ms to 45 ms. CPU and memory on the database instance are well below their limits. Which is the MOST likely root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The database instance class is undersized for the current workload."},{"id":"b","text":"The provisioned IOPS or storage throughput limit has been reached, causing I/O queuing."},{"id":"c","text":"The application's connection pool is exhausted, preventing new database sessions."},{"id":"d","text":"A recent schema migration introduced a missing index, causing full table scans."},{"id":"e","text":"The database's automatic backup process is running during peak business hours."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The key clue is that CPU and memory are healthy while I/O latency has spiked dramatically (2 ms to 45 ms). This pattern is a classic indicator of storage I/O saturation—the volume has reached its provisioned IOPS or throughput ceiling, so I/O requests queue up and wait. The fix is to increase provisioned IOPS, upgrade to a higher-performance storage tier, or optimize query patterns to reduce I/O. An undersized instance class (a) would typically show CPU or memory pressure first. Connection pool exhaustion (c) would surface as connection errors or timeouts in application logs, not storage latency. A missing index (d) could cause full scans and high CPU, not pure I/O latency spikes in isolation. Backup processes (e) can introduce some I/O overhead but rarely raise latency by an order of magnitude on properly configured cloud databases.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/MonitoringOverview.html","label":"AWS RDS – Monitoring I/O and Storage"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-sql/database/monitor-tune-overview","label":"Azure SQL Database – Performance Monitoring"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Users report that application response times have degraded significantly over the past 24 hours. A cloud administrator checks the managed relational database and finds that storage I/O latency has increased from 2 ms to 45 ms. CPU and memory on the database instance are well below their limits. Which is the MOST likely root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator is troubleshooting a failed deployment pipeline. The CI/CD system returns an error stating that it cannot pull a container image from the private container registry. The pipeline worked successfully yesterday. No changes were made to the registry. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The container registry endpoint URL was changed by the cloud provider."},{"id":"b","text":"The service account or IAM role used by the pipeline has had its registry read permissions revoked or its credentials have expired."},{"id":"c","text":"The container image has been corrupted and must be rebuilt."},{"id":"d","text":"The CI/CD runner node does not have enough disk space to store the image layers."},{"id":"e","text":"The registry is in a different availability zone than the CI/CD runner."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When a pipeline that previously worked suddenly cannot pull from a private registry—with no changes made to the registry—the most common culprit is an authentication or authorization failure. Service account tokens, IAM role policies, or registry credentials (such as Docker config secrets) can expire, be rotated, or have permissions modified inadvertently by another administrator or an automated compliance process. The administrator should verify that the service account's credentials are valid, that the IAM policy still grants the registry read action, and that any secrets stored in the CI/CD platform match current credentials. Cloud providers do not arbitrarily change registry endpoint URLs (a). A corrupted image (c) would produce a different error (checksum mismatch) and would affect all users, not just the pipeline. Disk space (d) would produce a 'no space left on device' error. Availability zones (e) do not restrict container registry access within the same region.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECR/latest/userguide/registry_auth.html","label":"AWS ECR – Private Registry Authentication"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/container-registry/container-registry-authentication","label":"Azure Container Registry – Authentication Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator is troubleshooting a failed deployment pipeline. The CI/CD system returns an error stating that it cannot pull a container image from the private container registry. The pipeline worked successfully yesterday. No changes were made to the registry. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud storage bucket that hosts a static website was working correctly, but users now receive HTTP 403 Forbidden errors when attempting to browse the site. No application code changes were made. Which of the following changes would MOST likely have caused this issue?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The bucket's static website hosting feature was accidentally disabled."},{"id":"b","text":"A bucket policy or ACL change removed public read access from the bucket objects."},{"id":"c","text":"The index document file was renamed in the bucket."},{"id":"d","text":"The cloud provider's object storage service is experiencing a regional degradation."},{"id":"e","text":"The bucket was moved to a different storage class, which does not support static hosting."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An HTTP 403 Forbidden response from a static website hosted in object storage means the request is reaching the storage service but is being denied at the access-control layer. The most frequent operational cause—particularly when nothing in the application changed—is a modification to the bucket policy or object ACLs that removed the 'public read' permission. Many cloud providers now enforce 'block public access' settings that, if enabled, override individual bucket policies and deny all anonymous reads. Disabling static website hosting (a) would typically return a 404 or redirect rather than a 403. Renaming the index document (c) causes a 404 for the root path, not a 403. A regional degradation (d) would affect many customers and produce varied errors, not a consistent 403. Storage classes (e) do not restrict static website hosting functionality in major cloud platforms.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/troubleshoot-403-errors.html","label":"AWS S3 – Troubleshooting Access Denied Errors"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/troubleshooting","label":"Google Cloud Storage – Troubleshooting Requests"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud storage bucket that hosts a static website was working correctly, but users now receive HTTP 403 Forbidden errors when attempting to browse the site. No application code changes were made. Which of the following changes would MOST likely have caused this issue?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator is investigating why a scheduled serverless function that aggregates daily sales data is silently failing—it completes without error messages but produces no output. Logs show the function starts and stops within the expected time window. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The function's execution timeout is too short and is being silently terminated before it can write output."},{"id":"b","text":"The function runtime version has been deprecated by the cloud provider."},{"id":"c","text":"The function lacks the necessary IAM permissions to read from the source data store or write to the destination, causing the operation to return empty results rather than an error."},{"id":"d","text":"The function trigger schedule uses an incorrect cron expression, causing it to run at the wrong time."},{"id":"e","text":"The function's reserved concurrency limit is set to zero."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Silent failures that produce no output but complete without exceptions are a hallmark of insufficient IAM permissions on serverless functions. When a function attempts to read from a source (e.g., a database, another bucket, or an API) and lacks read permission, the SDK may return an empty result set or silently swallow a permission error depending on how error handling is coded, resulting in the function writing zero records. Similarly, if write permissions are missing, the function may process data internally but fail silently when attempting to persist results. An administrator should verify that the function's execution role has the correct read/write policies attached. A timeout (a) would appear in logs as a timeout error or truncated log stream. A deprecated runtime (b) typically raises an invocation error. An incorrect cron expression (d) would prevent the function from running at all during the expected window. A concurrency limit of zero (e) would prevent all invocations and generate throttle errors.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/lambda-intro-execution-role.html","label":"AWS Lambda – Execution Role Permissions"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/functions/docs/concepts/iam","label":"Google Cloud Functions – IAM and Access Control"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator is investigating why a scheduled serverless function that aggregates daily sales data is silently failing—it completes without error messages but produces no output. Logs show the function starts and stops within the expected time window. Which of the following is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);

