INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A solutions architect is designing a multi-tier web application on a public cloud platform. The application must remain available even if an entire data center becomes unavailable. Which architectural approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy all tiers within a single Availability Zone and configure auto-scaling groups."},{"id":"b","text":"Distribute each application tier across multiple Availability Zones with load balancers at each tier."},{"id":"c","text":"Use a single large virtual machine with redundant network interface cards."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable automatic snapshots of all virtual machines on a daily schedule."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Distributing application tiers across multiple Availability Zones (AZs) ensures that if one data center (AZ) fails, the other AZs continue to serve traffic. Load balancers at each tier route requests only to healthy instances. A single AZ deployment (option A) does not protect against a full data center outage. Redundant NICs (option C) address network card failure, not data center failure. Snapshots (option D) support recovery but do not maintain availability during an outage.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-regions-availability-zones.html","label":"AWS – Regions and Availability Zones"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A solutions architect is designing a multi-tier web application on a public cloud platform. The application must remain available even if an entire data center becomes unavailable. Which architectural approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization needs to host a workload that processes highly sensitive financial data. The compliance team requires dedicated physical hardware with no shared tenancy. Which cloud deployment model BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Public cloud with default multi-tenant virtual machines"},{"id":"b","text":"Community cloud shared among financial industry partners"},{"id":"c","text":"Dedicated hosts or bare-metal instances in a public cloud"},{"id":"d","text":"Serverless functions deployed in a public cloud region"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Dedicated hosts and bare-metal instances provide a physical server exclusively assigned to a single customer, eliminating shared tenancy. This satisfies hardware isolation requirements imposed by financial compliance frameworks. Standard multi-tenant VMs (option A) share underlying physical hardware. Community clouds (option B) still involve shared tenancy among multiple organizations. Serverless functions (option D) are inherently multi-tenant and abstract away the underlying hardware entirely.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/dedicated-hosts-overview.html","label":"AWS – Dedicated Hosts"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/dedicated-hosts","label":"Azure – Dedicated Hosts Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization needs to host a workload that processes highly sensitive financial data. The compliance team requires dedicated physical hardware with no shared tenancy. Which cloud deployment model BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is selecting a storage tier for a data archival solution. The data must be retained for seven years but is rarely accessed. Cost optimization is the primary concern. Which storage class BEST fits this scenario?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"High-performance SSD-backed block storage"},{"id":"b","text":"Standard object storage with frequent-access tier"},{"id":"c","text":"Cold or archive object storage tier with retrieval latency measured in hours"},{"id":"d","text":"In-memory distributed cache"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cold or archive storage tiers (such as AWS S3 Glacier Deep Archive or Azure Archive Storage) are designed for data that is rarely retrieved and must be kept long-term. They offer the lowest per-GB storage cost in exchange for higher retrieval latency and cost. High-performance SSD block storage (option A) is expensive and optimized for low-latency I/O workloads. Standard frequent-access object storage (option B) is cheaper than block storage but significantly more expensive than archive tiers for cold data. In-memory caches (option D) are volatile, costly, and not suited for long-term retention.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/s3/storage-classes/","label":"AWS S3 Storage Classes"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/access-tiers-overview","label":"Azure Blob Storage Access Tiers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is selecting a storage tier for a data archival solution. The data must be retained for seven years but is rarely accessed. Cost optimization is the primary concern. Which storage class BEST fits this scenario?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is designing a cloud architecture that must automatically add compute resources during peak business hours and remove them during off-peak hours to minimize cost. Which cloud characteristic DIRECTLY enables this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Resource pooling"},{"id":"b","text":"Measured service"},{"id":"c","text":"Rapid elasticity"},{"id":"d","text":"Broad network access"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Rapid elasticity is the NIST-defined cloud characteristic that allows resources to be provisioned and released quickly—automatically or manually—to scale with demand. This directly enables adding capacity during peak hours and releasing it during off-peak hours. Resource pooling (option A) refers to serving multiple consumers from shared resources but does not describe the dynamic scaling behavior itself. Measured service (option B) relates to metering and billing for actual usage. Broad network access (option D) describes the ability to access services over standard network protocols from diverse client devices.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-145 – The NIST Definition of Cloud Computing"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is designing a cloud architecture that must automatically add compute resources during peak business hours and remove them during off-peak hours to minimize cost. Which cloud characteristic DIRECTLY enables this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An architect is designing a loosely coupled cloud application. Instead of services calling each other directly over synchronous HTTP, messages are placed in a queue for downstream consumers to process independently. Which design pattern does this BEST describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Monolithic architecture pattern"},{"id":"b","text":"Message queue / asynchronous messaging pattern"},{"id":"c","text":"Tightly coupled request-response pattern"},{"id":"d","text":"Data replication pattern"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The message queue pattern decouples producers and consumers: producers drop messages into a queue and continue processing without waiting for a response; consumers retrieve and process messages independently. This improves resilience and scalability. Monolithic architecture (option A) packages all components together with no inherent decoupling. Tightly coupled request-response (option C) is the synchronous direct-call approach the question states is being avoided. Data replication (option D) is a storage and availability pattern unrelated to service communication decoupling.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/welcome.html","label":"AWS – Message Queue Architecture Overview (SQS)"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/queues/storage-queues-introduction","label":"Azure – Queue Storage Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An architect is designing a loosely coupled cloud application. Instead of services calling each other directly over synchronous HTTP, messages are placed in a queue for downstream consumers to process independently. Which design pattern does this BEST describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud architecture review, a team needs to decide where to run a workload that requires extremely low and predictable network latency to on-premises industrial equipment. The workload cannot tolerate the round-trip time to a central cloud region. Which architectural approach BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy the workload in the cloud provider's furthest geographic region to distribute load globally."},{"id":"b","text":"Use an edge computing or cloud provider local zone/wavelength deployment closer to the equipment."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the VM instance size in the central cloud region to reduce processing time."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable content delivery network (CDN) caching for the industrial data stream."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Edge computing and cloud provider constructs such as AWS Local Zones, AWS Wavelength, or Azure Edge Zones push compute capacity physically closer to end devices or on-premises equipment, dramatically reducing network latency. The furthest geographic region (option A) would increase, not decrease, latency. Increasing VM size (option C) reduces computation time but cannot compensate for network round-trip latency to a distant region. CDNs (option D) cache static web content for end users and are not designed for low-latency industrial control or real-time data processing workloads.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/local-zones/latest/ug/what-is-aws-local-zones.html","label":"AWS Local Zones Overview"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/networking/edge-zones-overview","label":"Azure Edge Zones Overview"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud architecture review, a team needs to decide where to run a workload that requires extremely low and predictable network latency to on-premises industrial equipment. The workload cannot tolerate the round-trip time to a central cloud region. Which architectural approach BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations engineer needs to ensure that a production workload automatically recovers from a single Availability Zone failure within the same region without manual intervention. Which operational approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy the workload in a single AZ and create a runbook for manual failover to a secondary AZ."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure an auto-scaling group spanning multiple Availability Zones with health-check-based instance replacement."},{"id":"c","text":"Take nightly snapshots of the workload and restore them to a secondary AZ when an outage is detected."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable cross-region replication and update DNS records to point to the replica during a failure."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Configuring an auto-scaling group (or equivalent multi-AZ managed service) that spans multiple Availability Zones allows the platform to automatically replace unhealthy instances and redistribute load without human intervention, satisfying the automatic, same-region recovery requirement. Option A requires manual action. Option C introduces significant RTO due to the snapshot restore process and still requires manual detection. Option D addresses cross-region recovery, which exceeds the stated scope and typically requires additional manual or scripted DNS changes.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/auto-scaling-benefits.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling Across Availability Zones"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations engineer needs to ensure that a production workload automatically recovers from a single Availability Zone failure within the same region without manual intervention. Which operational approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization's SLA requires an RTO of 15 minutes and an RPO of 5 minutes for a critical database tier hosted in a public cloud. Which combination of operational strategies BEST meets both targets?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Daily full backups stored in object storage with a tested restoration runbook."},{"id":"b","text":"Synchronous replication to a standby instance in the same region combined with automated failover orchestration."},{"id":"c","text":"Asynchronous replication to a cross-region read replica with manual promotion steps."},{"id":"d","text":"Weekly snapshots with incremental daily snapshots and a cold-standby instance."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Synchronous replication ensures zero or near-zero data loss (meeting the 5-minute RPO, actually bettering it), and automated failover orchestration ensures the new primary is promoted and accessible within the 15-minute RTO window. Option A's daily backups far exceed both targets. Option C's asynchronous replication introduces replication lag that may violate the RPO, and manual promotion steps risk missing the RTO. Option D's weekly/incremental schedule and cold standby cannot meet either target reliably.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-sql/database/business-continuity-high-availability-disaster-recover-hadr-overview","label":"Azure SQL Database Business Continuity Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization's SLA requires an RTO of 15 minutes and an RPO of 5 minutes for a critical database tier hosted in a public cloud. Which combination of operational strategies BEST meets both targets?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator observes that virtual machine CPU utilization consistently reaches 95% during business hours but drops to 10% overnight. Which operational feature should be implemented to optimize both performance and cost?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Right-size the VM to a larger instance type permanently to handle peak load at all times."},{"id":"b","text":"Implement scheduled scaling policies that increase capacity before peak hours and decrease it after business hours."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable detailed monitoring only and review the data weekly to decide on manual resizing."},{"id":"d","text":"Migrate the workload to a reserved instance with the largest available vCPU count."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Scheduled scaling policies allow the organization to proactively add compute capacity before the known peak window and reduce it afterward, directly addressing the predictable load pattern while avoiding the cost of running over-provisioned resources overnight. Option A wastes money on excess capacity during off-hours. Option C is reactive and does not automate cost or performance optimization. Option D over-provisions and incurs unnecessary reserved-instance costs for capacity that is idle 60%+ of the time.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/scheduled_scaling.html","label":"AWS Scheduled Scaling for EC2 Auto Scaling"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator observes that virtual machine CPU utilization consistently reaches 95% during business hours but drops to 10% overnight. Which operational feature should be implemented to optimize both performance and cost?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team wants to deploy application updates to a cloud environment while minimizing user-facing downtime and retaining the ability to roll back instantly if a defect is detected post-deployment. Which deployment and operations strategy BEST fulfills these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Perform a maintenance-window deployment that replaces all instances simultaneously."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a blue/green deployment model where traffic is shifted to the new environment and the old environment is kept warm for rollback."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy directly to production and rely on application logs to detect defects after the fact."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a canary deployment that gradually replaces all instances over 72 hours with no rollback plan."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Blue/green deployments maintain two identical environments; traffic is routed to the new (green) environment while the old (blue) environment remains live and warm. If a defect is found, traffic is immediately switched back to blue with near-zero downtime, fulfilling both the minimal-downtime and instant-rollback requirements. Option A causes complete downtime during the replacement window. Option C has no structured rollback mechanism. Option D describes a partial canary approach but explicitly states no rollback plan, violating the stated requirement.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/blue-green-deployments/introduction.html","label":"AWS Blue/Green Deployments"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team wants to deploy application updates to a cloud environment while minimizing user-facing downtime and retaining the ability to roll back instantly if a defect is detected post-deployment. Which deployment and operations strategy BEST fulfills these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations team is tasked with establishing a tagging strategy across all cloud resources to improve cost allocation and operational visibility. Which element is MOST critical to include in the tagging policy to ensure accurate charge-back reporting to business units?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A tag that records the date the resource was last patched."},{"id":"b","text":"A mandatory cost-center or business-unit identifier tag enforced through a cloud policy engine."},{"id":"c","text":"A tag containing the public IP address of each resource."},{"id":"d","text":"A tag that stores the VM's operating system version."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Accurate charge-back reporting requires that every billable resource be associated with the responsible business unit or cost center. Making a cost-center tag mandatory and enforcing it via a policy engine (such as AWS Service Control Policies, Azure Policy, or GCP Organization Policies) prevents untagged resource spend from being unallocable. Option A is an operational/patch-management tag with no billing significance. Option C's IP address tag has no financial attribution value. Option D's OS version tag is useful for patch compliance, not charge-back.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cost-management-billing/costs/cost-mgt-best-practices","label":"Azure Cost Management Tagging Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations team is tasked with establishing a tagging strategy across all cloud resources to improve cost allocation and operational visibility. Which element is MOST critical to include in the tagging policy to ensure accurate charge-back reporting to business units?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is reviewing monitoring dashboards and notices that application response time has increased by 300% over the past hour even though CPU and memory metrics appear normal. Which monitoring data source should be investigated FIRST to isolate the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Hypervisor CPU steal-time metrics."},{"id":"b","text":"Network throughput and latency metrics at the load balancer and between application tiers."},{"id":"c","text":"Disk read IOPS on the operating system boot volume."},{"id":"d","text":"Number of active SSH sessions on the affected instances."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When response time degrades significantly but CPU and memory are healthy, the bottleneck commonly lies in network latency or throughput between components (e.g., between the load balancer, application servers, and database). Reviewing load-balancer latency, inter-tier network metrics, and connection pool saturation would reveal queuing, packet loss, or bandwidth saturation. Option A (CPU steal-time) is relevant when CPU appears artificially low but would show up as elevated in adjusted metrics. Option C (boot volume IOPS) rarely impacts application response time in isolation. Option D (SSH sessions) is an administrative/security concern unrelated to application latency.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/monitoring/alerts/using-alerting-ui","label":"Google Cloud Monitoring — Latency Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is reviewing monitoring dashboards and notices that application response time has increased by 300% over the past hour even though CPU and memory metrics appear normal. Which monitoring data source should be investigated FIRST to isolate the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team must establish a patch management process for a fleet of 500 Linux virtual machines running production workloads in a public cloud. Which approach BEST balances security compliance with operational stability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply all available patches immediately to every instance simultaneously as soon as they are released by the vendor."},{"id":"b","text":"Test patches in a non-production environment first, then use a rolling deployment with automated health checks to apply them to production instances in batches."},{"id":"c","text":"Defer all patching until the annual maintenance window to reduce operational disruption."},{"id":"d","text":"Only patch instances that have been explicitly flagged by end users as experiencing problems."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A staged patch process—test in non-production, then roll out in production batches with automated health checks—ensures that regressions are caught before they affect the entire fleet, while keeping security posture current. Option A risks introducing a breaking patch to all 500 instances at once with no recovery option. Option C leaves the fleet exposed to known vulnerabilities for up to a year. Option D is reactive and relies on user-reported issues rather than proactive security hygiene, missing silent exploits entirely.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-patch.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team must establish a patch management process for a fleet of 500 Linux virtual machines running production workloads in a public cloud. Which approach BEST balances security compliance with operational stability?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations team is designing a log management strategy for a multi-account cloud environment. The security team requires that application logs be retained for 13 months to satisfy a regulatory audit requirement, and that logs cannot be altered or deleted by application teams. Which combination of operational controls BEST enforces these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store logs locally on each virtual machine and instruct application teams not to delete them."},{"id":"b","text":"Stream logs to a centralized object storage bucket in a dedicated logging account with Object Lock (WORM) enabled and a lifecycle policy set to 13 months."},{"id":"c","text":"Forward logs to an application team-managed S3 bucket with a versioning policy and a verbal agreement on retention."},{"id":"d","text":"Archive logs to a shared file system with read/write permissions granted to all accounts and a 13-month manual deletion schedule."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Centralizing logs in an isolated logging account prevents application teams from accessing or modifying them. Enabling Object Lock (Write-Once-Read-Many / WORM) on the bucket makes objects immutable for the defined retention period, ensuring logs cannot be altered or deleted—satisfying both the regulatory retention requirement and the tamper-proof control. Option A relies on local storage that application teams control, making deletion trivially easy. Option C puts the bucket under application team control, which undermines the immutability requirement. Option D grants write access to all accounts, which allows tampering and does not enforce WORM semantics.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lock.html","label":"AWS S3 Object Lock — Using S3 Object Lock"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/immutable-storage-overview","label":"Azure Immutable Blob Storage"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations team is designing a log management strategy for a multi-account cloud environment. The security team requires that application logs be retained for 13 months to satisfy a regulatory audit requirement, and that logs cannot be altered or deleted by application teams. Which combination of operational controls BEST enforces these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud security engineer is tasked with ensuring that all data stored in an object storage service remains unreadable if the storage provider is compromised. The organization holds its own master keys and requires that no third party ever has access to the plaintext key material. Which encryption approach BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Server-Side Encryption with provider-managed keys (SSE-PMK)"},{"id":"b","text":"Client-Side Encryption with customer-managed keys stored in an on-premises HSM"},{"id":"c","text":"Server-Side Encryption with a cloud-provider key management service (SSE-KMS) using provider-generated CMKs"},{"id":"d","text":"Transport Layer Security (TLS) 1.3 applied to all object storage API calls"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Client-Side Encryption (CSE) with keys stored in an on-premises Hardware Security Module (HSM) means the data is encrypted before it ever leaves the customer's environment. The cloud provider receives only ciphertext and never has access to the plaintext key material, fully satisfying the requirement. SSE-PMK (option A) delegates key management entirely to the provider. SSE-KMS with provider-generated CMKs (option C) still allows the provider to access the key material under certain conditions. TLS (option D) protects data in transit only, not data at rest.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives – Security Domain"},{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-111/final","label":"NIST SP 800-111: Guide to Storage Encryption Technologies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud security engineer is tasked with ensuring that all data stored in an object storage service remains unreadable if the storage provider is compromised. The organization holds its own master keys and requires that no third party ever has access to the plaintext key material. Which encryption approach BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization operating a multi-tenant SaaS platform on a public cloud discovers that a misconfigured IAM policy allows one tenant's service account to list and read S3-equivalent object buckets belonging to other tenants. Which security principle was MOST directly violated?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Defense in depth"},{"id":"b","text":"Least privilege"},{"id":"c","text":"Non-repudiation"},{"id":"d","text":"Availability"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The principle of least privilege states that an identity should be granted only the minimum permissions required to perform its intended function. Allowing one tenant's service account to access another tenant's buckets far exceeds the necessary permissions, directly violating least privilege. Defense in depth (option A) refers to layering multiple security controls, which is a separate concept. Non-repudiation (option C) concerns the ability to prove the origin of an action, not access control scoping. Availability (option D) is a CIA triad property concerned with uptime, not access boundaries.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives – Security Domain"},{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-190/final","label":"NIST SP 800-190: Application Container Security Guide (IAM Least Privilege Context)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization operating a multi-tenant SaaS platform on a public cloud discovers that a misconfigured IAM policy allows one tenant's service account to list and read S3-equivalent object buckets belonging to other tenants. Which security principle was MOST directly violated?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security analyst reviews logs and notices that an attacker successfully retrieved temporary credentials from a cloud instance's metadata service endpoint (169.254.169.254) by exploiting a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability in a web application. Which compensating control would MOST effectively have prevented the credential theft via this specific attack vector?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enabling multi-factor authentication on the cloud management console"},{"id":"b","text":"Requiring IMDSv2 (instance metadata service version 2) with session-oriented requests"},{"id":"c","text":"Encrypting all application data at rest using customer-managed keys"},{"id":"d","text":"Deploying a Web Application Firewall (WAF) with OWASP ruleset"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$IMDSv2 requires a session-oriented PUT request to obtain a token before metadata can be read. A simple SSRF-driven GET request to 169.254.169.254 will be rejected because the attacker cannot perform the preliminary PUT through most SSRF vectors, preventing credential theft. MFA on the console (option A) protects human logins but does not affect metadata service access. Encryption at rest (option C) protects stored data but does nothing to prevent credential exfiltration through SSRF. A WAF (option D) can help mitigate SSRF patterns at the HTTP layer but is a general-purpose control; enforcing IMDSv2 is the direct, purpose-built mitigation for this specific attack path.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/configuring-instance-metadata-service.html","label":"AWS – Use IMDSv2 to mitigate SSRF attacks"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives – Security Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security analyst reviews logs and notices that an attacker successfully retrieved temporary credentials from a cloud instance's metadata service endpoint (169.254.169.254) by exploiting a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerability in a web application. Which compensating control would MOST effectively have prevented the credential theft via this specific attack vector?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A compliance officer requires that all administrative API calls made to the cloud control plane be logged, tamper-evident, and retained for a minimum of one year to satisfy an audit requirement. Which cloud-native service category BEST fulfills this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Network flow logs stored in a standard writable object storage bucket"},{"id":"b","text":"A cloud audit trail (control-plane activity log) delivered to a write-once, WORM-protected storage vault"},{"id":"c","text":"Application Performance Monitoring (APM) traces exported to a SIEM"},{"id":"d","text":"Virtual machine OS-level syslog forwarded to a log aggregation service"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cloud audit trails (e.g., AWS CloudTrail, Azure Activity Log, GCP Audit Logs) record all control-plane API calls with metadata such as caller identity, timestamp, and source IP. Delivering these logs to WORM-protected (Write Once Read Many) object storage ensures tamper-evidence and supports long-term retention, directly meeting audit requirements. Network flow logs (option A) capture packet-level metadata, not control-plane API actions, and a standard writable bucket is not tamper-evident. APM traces (option C) measure application performance, not administrative API activity. OS-level syslog (option D) records operating system events, not cloud control-plane calls, and would miss API actions made outside the VM.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-user-guide.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail Documentation – What is AWS CloudTrail?"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/essentials/activity-log","label":"Azure Monitor Activity Log Overview"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives – Security Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A compliance officer requires that all administrative API calls made to the cloud control plane be logged, tamper-evident, and retained for a minimum of one year to satisfy an audit requirement. Which cloud-native service category BEST fulfills this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevSecOps team wants to prevent secrets such as API keys and database passwords from being committed to a cloud-hosted source code repository. They want the control to be enforced automatically before code reaches the central repository. Which approach BEST achieves this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Manually reviewing every pull request for hardcoded credentials before merging"},{"id":"b","text":"Storing all secrets in environment variables defined in the application source code"},{"id":"c","text":"Implementing a pre-commit or pre-receive git hook that runs a secrets-scanning tool and rejects commits containing detected secrets"},{"id":"d","text":"Encrypting the entire repository using repository-level encryption provided by the source control platform"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A pre-commit hook runs locally on the developer's machine before a commit is created, while a pre-receive hook enforces the check server-side before the push is accepted. Either configuration automatically blocks secrets from entering the repository without relying on human review. Secrets-scanning tools (e.g., git-secrets, detect-secrets, truffleHog) can identify patterns matching API keys, passwords, and tokens. Manual review (option A) is prone to human error and does not scale. Storing secrets in source-code environment variables (option B) still embeds them in the codebase. Repository-level encryption (option D) protects data at rest but does nothing to prevent a secret from being committed in plaintext—anyone with repository access can still read it.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Secrets_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html","label":"OWASP – Secrets Management Cheat Sheet"},{"url":"https://docs.github.com/en/code-security/secret-scanning/about-secret-scanning","label":"GitHub Docs – About secret scanning"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives – Security Domain"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevSecOps team wants to prevent secrets such as API keys and database passwords from being committed to a cloud-hosted source code repository. They want the control to be enforced automatically before code reaches the central repository. Which approach BEST achieves this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator notices that a production virtual machine in a public cloud environment is intermittently losing network connectivity. Packet loss is observed, but CPU and memory utilization remain normal. Which troubleshooting step should the administrator perform FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Resize the VM to a larger instance type to improve network throughput"},{"id":"b","text":"Review cloud provider network flow logs and check for throttling or bandwidth limits on the instance type"},{"id":"c","text":"Immediately migrate the VM to an on-premises environment"},{"id":"d","text":"Reinstall the guest operating system on the affected VM"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When intermittent packet loss occurs without CPU or memory anomalies, the first step is to consult network flow logs and verify whether bandwidth throttling or network limits associated with the instance type are being reached. Cloud providers enforce per-instance network caps; reviewing flow logs pinpoints whether limits are being hit before more disruptive actions are taken. Resizing without data is premature, migrating to on-premises is extreme, and reinstalling the OS does not address a network-layer issue.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/monitoring-network-performance-ena.html","label":"AWS: Monitor network performance for EC2 instances"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator notices that a production virtual machine in a public cloud environment is intermittently losing network connectivity. Packet loss is observed, but CPU and memory utilization remain normal. Which troubleshooting step should the administrator perform FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Users are reporting that an application hosted on a cloud-based virtual machine takes over 60 seconds to respond after being idle for 10 minutes. The VM shows normal CPU and RAM usage during the delay. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The cloud provider is experiencing a regional outage"},{"id":"b","text":"The VM is configured with auto-scaling that is adding new instances"},{"id":"c","text":"The VM or application is configured to hibernate or suspend after a period of inactivity, causing a cold-start delay"},{"id":"d","text":"The security group is blocking inbound traffic after idle periods"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A delay that occurs specifically after a period of inactivity is a classic symptom of a hibernation, suspension, or application cold-start configuration. Many cloud platforms and application runtimes (e.g., serverless containers, stopped instances) must be 'warmed up' when traffic resumes. A regional outage would cause complete unavailability, auto-scaling adds instances continuously rather than after idle periods, and security groups are stateful and do not selectively block traffic after inactivity.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/Hibernate.html","label":"AWS: Hibernate your Amazon EC2 instance"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Users are reporting that an application hosted on a cloud-based virtual machine takes over 60 seconds to respond after being idle for 10 minutes. The VM shows normal CPU and RAM usage during the delay. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer deploys a new container image to a Kubernetes cluster. The pods enter a CrashLoopBackOff state shortly after deployment. Which command should the engineer run FIRST to determine the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl delete pod <pod-name>"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl cordon <node-name>"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl scale deployment <name> --replicas=0"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The CrashLoopBackOff state means the container starts and then crashes repeatedly. Running 'kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous' retrieves the logs from the most recently terminated container instance, which is essential for identifying application-level errors causing the crash. Deleting the pod only restarts it without gathering information. Cordoning the node prevents new scheduling but does not diagnose the issue. Scaling to zero removes the workload entirely and loses diagnostic opportunity.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-application/debug-running-pod/","label":"Kubernetes: Debug Running Pods"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer deploys a new container image to a Kubernetes cluster. The pods enter a CrashLoopBackOff state shortly after deployment. Which command should the engineer run FIRST to determine the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization's cloud-hosted web application is returning HTTP 503 errors during peak business hours but works normally at other times. Auto-scaling is enabled. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The TLS certificate has expired on the load balancer"},{"id":"b","text":"The auto-scaling warm-up period is too long, causing new instances to not become healthy before traffic arrives"},{"id":"c","text":"The application's database credentials are incorrect"},{"id":"d","text":"The cloud provider's DNS service is misconfigured"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$HTTP 503 (Service Unavailable) during peak hours when auto-scaling is enabled typically indicates that new instances are being launched but take too long to pass health checks and enter service, leaving the load balancer with insufficient healthy backends. This is a classic auto-scaling warm-up or health-check threshold misconfiguration. An expired TLS certificate causes HTTPS errors consistently, not just at peak times. Incorrect database credentials would produce application errors at all times. DNS misconfiguration would result in resolution failures, not 503 responses.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-troubleshooting.html","label":"AWS: Troubleshoot your Application Load Balancer"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization's cloud-hosted web application is returning HTTP 503 errors during peak business hours but works normally at other times. Auto-scaling is enabled. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is troubleshooting a storage issue where writes to a cloud object storage bucket are succeeding, but a downstream processing application cannot read the newly written objects for up to 30 seconds. No errors are returned. What cloud storage characteristic BEST explains this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Strong consistency enforced by a distributed lock manager"},{"id":"b","text":"Eventual consistency in the object storage service where reads after writes may not immediately reflect new data"},{"id":"c","text":"Object versioning causing the application to read older object versions"},{"id":"d","text":"Bucket policy denying the application's IAM role read access temporarily"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Eventual consistency is a well-known characteristic of distributed object storage systems. In an eventually consistent model, after a successful write, read operations may return stale or absent data for a short period until all replicas converge. This matches the described 30-second read delay with no errors. Strong consistency would not cause this delay. Object versioning would still surface the new object as the latest version immediately. A policy denial would produce an access error, not a silent read delay.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/Welcome.html#ConsistencyModel","label":"AWS S3: Consistency model"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is troubleshooting a storage issue where writes to a cloud object storage bucket are succeeding, but a downstream processing application cannot read the newly written objects for up to 30 seconds. No errors are returned. What cloud storage characteristic BEST explains this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A system administrator observes that cloud VM instances are being automatically terminated and replaced at random intervals, even though no scaling policies have been triggered and utilization metrics are within normal thresholds. Which feature is MOST likely responsible for this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Spot or preemptible instance reclamation by the cloud provider"},{"id":"b","text":"A scheduled maintenance reboot configured by the OS vendor"},{"id":"c","text":"A runbook automation script that is rotating SSH keys"},{"id":"d","text":"An expired reserved instance contract causing the VM to be released"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Spot instances (AWS) and preemptible VMs (Google Cloud) are low-cost instance types that can be reclaimed by the cloud provider at any time when capacity is needed elsewhere. This results in random terminations and replacements unrelated to scaling policies or utilization. Scheduled OS maintenance reboots restart VMs but do not terminate and replace them. SSH key rotation scripts do not terminate instances. Expired reserved contracts affect billing but do not cause instance termination.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/spot-interruptions.html","label":"AWS: Spot Instance interruptions"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/instances/preemptible","label":"Google Cloud: Preemptible VM instances"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A system administrator observes that cloud VM instances are being automatically terminated and replaced at random intervals, even though no scaling policies have been triggered and utilization metrics are within normal thresholds. Which feature is MOST likely responsible for this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator deploys an application across two cloud regions for high availability. Users in Region B report significantly higher latency than users in Region A, even though both regions show similar server-side response times. What should the administrator investigate FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the application's database is only deployed in Region A, forcing Region B to make cross-region database calls"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether the cloud provider has deprecated the Region B instance type"},{"id":"c","text":"Whether the application code has a memory leak in Region B"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the TLS handshake version differs between the two regions"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When server-side response times are equal but client-perceived latency is higher in one region, the most common cause is a dependency (such as a database, cache, or API) that is located only in the low-latency region, forcing the other region to make cross-region calls. This adds network round-trip time invisible to per-region server metrics. Instance type deprecation does not directly affect latency. A memory leak would manifest as degrading response times over time server-side. TLS version differences are unlikely to produce region-specific sustained latency.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-multi-region-fundamentals/aws-multi-region-fundamentals.html","label":"AWS: Building a Multi-Region Architecture"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator deploys an application across two cloud regions for high availability. Users in Region B report significantly higher latency than users in Region A, even though both regions show similar server-side response times. What should the administrator investigate FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud-hosted application's deployment pipeline begins failing with 'insufficient permissions' errors when attempting to push container images to a private registry. The pipeline worked successfully yesterday with no code changes. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The container image exceeds the registry's storage quota"},{"id":"b","text":"A recently rotated or expired service account credential used by the pipeline is no longer valid"},{"id":"c","text":"The private registry's firewall rules were updated to block all inbound traffic"},{"id":"d","text":"The container runtime version on the build agent is incompatible with the registry"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An 'insufficient permissions' error that appears suddenly without code changes strongly suggests a credential issue—specifically a service account token, API key, or password that has been rotated, expired, or revoked since the last successful run. Exceeding storage quota would return a quota or storage error, not a permissions error. A firewall blocking all traffic would produce a connection timeout, not an authentication failure. Runtime version incompatibility would manifest as a different type of error unrelated to permissions.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/artifact-registry/docs/troubleshooting","label":"Google Cloud: Troubleshoot Artifact Registry authentication"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud-hosted application's deployment pipeline begins failing with 'insufficient permissions' errors when attempting to push container images to a private registry. The pipeline worked successfully yesterday with no code changes. What is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is investigating why a serverless function is consistently timing out only when processing large input payloads above 5 MB, while small payloads complete in under one second. The function's maximum execution timeout is set to 30 seconds. What should the engineer check FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Whether the function's allocated memory is too low, causing slow execution for CPU-intensive processing of large payloads"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether the cloud region has a known outage logged in the provider's status page"},{"id":"c","text":"Whether the function's concurrency limit is set to 1"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the function's deployment package is too large to be loaded at runtime"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In most serverless platforms, memory allocation is directly tied to CPU performance. Insufficient memory limits the CPU available to the function, causing large-payload processing (which is CPU and memory intensive) to be disproportionately slow and exceed timeouts. Small payloads complete quickly because they need minimal compute resources. A regional outage would affect all payload sizes equally. A concurrency limit of 1 would cause queuing delays, not CPU-bound timeouts on a single invocation. Deployment package size affects cold-start time, not per-invocation execution duration.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/configuration-memory.html","label":"AWS Lambda: Function memory and CPU power"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is investigating why a serverless function is consistently timing out only when processing large input payloads above 5 MB, while small payloads complete in under one second. The function's maximum execution timeout is set to 30 seconds. What should the engineer check FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After migrating a workload from on-premises to a cloud IaaS environment, the operations team notices that the virtual machine's disk I/O performance is significantly lower than expected despite choosing a high-performance SSD-backed volume. Benchmarking shows the throughput is throttled. What is the MOST likely explanation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The VM instance type's I/O credit balance has been exhausted due to burstable storage provisioning"},{"id":"b","text":"The cloud provider does not support SSD volumes for virtual machines"},{"id":"c","text":"The on-premises storage driver is incompatible with the cloud hypervisor"},{"id":"d","text":"The VM's virtual NIC is saturating, causing disk I/O to be queued"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Many cloud providers offer burstable storage volumes (e.g., AWS gp2/gp3, Azure Standard SSD) that accumulate I/O credits during idle periods and allow bursting. When I/O credit balances are exhausted—common with sustained heavy workloads post-migration—throughput is throttled to the baseline rate, which can be far lower than the burst maximum. Cloud providers universally support SSD volumes for VMs, so that is incorrect. On-premises storage drivers are replaced by cloud-native virtio or paravirtual drivers after migration. NIC saturation would throttle network, not disk I/O.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/ebs/latest/userguide/ebs-volume-types.html","label":"AWS: Amazon EBS volume types and I/O credits"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/disks-performance","label":"Azure: Managed disk performance tiers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After migrating a workload from on-premises to a cloud IaaS environment, the operations team notices that the virtual machine's disk I/O performance is significantly lower than expected despite choosing a high-performance SSD-backed volume. Benchmarking shows the throughput is throttled. What is the MOST likely explanation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a multi-tier web application and needs to ensure that the database tier is NOT directly accessible from the internet while still allowing the application tier to query it. Which deployment approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy the database in a public subnet and use a security group to block all inbound traffic from 0.0.0.0/0"},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy the database in a private subnet with no internet gateway route, and use security group rules that allow inbound traffic only from the application tier's security group"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy the database in a public subnet and enable network ACLs that deny all traffic on port 443"},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy the database in a private subnet and assign it an Elastic IP address to facilitate connectivity with the application tier"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Placing the database in a private subnet with no route to an internet gateway ensures no direct internet reachability. Restricting inbound security group rules to only the application tier's security group enforces least-privilege network access between tiers. Option A is risky because a misconfigured rule could expose the database publicly. Option C blocks HTTPS but not database ports. Option D defeats the isolation purpose by assigning a public IP.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html","label":"AWS VPC Subnets and Routing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a multi-tier web application and needs to ensure that the database tier is NOT directly accessible from the internet while still allowing the application tier to query it. Which deployment approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud deployment, an operations team wants to use an Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tool to provision resources in a repeatable and version-controlled manner. The team's environment is primarily Microsoft Azure. Which tool is MOST purpose-built for declarative, idempotent deployments on Azure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS CloudFormation"},{"id":"b","text":"Azure Resource Manager (ARM) templates"},{"id":"c","text":"Ansible playbooks using the shell module"},{"id":"d","text":"Bash scripts invoked through the Azure portal"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Azure Resource Manager (ARM) templates are Microsoft's native declarative IaC format for Azure, providing idempotent, repeatable deployments. AWS CloudFormation is specific to AWS. Ansible can work with Azure but uses an imperative model by default and is not purpose-built for Azure. Bash scripts are not declarative and do not natively guarantee idempotency.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-resource-manager/templates/overview","label":"What are ARM templates? – Microsoft Learn"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud deployment, an operations team wants to use an Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tool to provision resources in a repeatable and version-controlled manner. The team's environment is primarily Microsoft Azure. Which tool is MOST purpose-built for declarative, idempotent deployments on Azure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is setting up a CI/CD pipeline for a containerized microservices application hosted on a Kubernetes cluster. They want zero-downtime deployments where traffic shifts gradually from the old version to the new version. Which deployment strategy BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Recreate deployment strategy"},{"id":"b","text":"Blue/green deployment strategy"},{"id":"c","text":"Canary deployment strategy"},{"id":"d","text":"Immutable deployment strategy"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A canary deployment gradually shifts a small percentage of traffic to the new version and incrementally increases it, allowing real-time monitoring and rollback before full rollout — ideal for zero-downtime gradual traffic shifting. Recreate strategy causes downtime by terminating all old pods first. Blue/green switches traffic all at once rather than gradually. Immutable deployment replaces entire infrastructure but does not by itself provide gradual traffic shifting.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/#strategy","label":"Kubernetes Deployment Strategies"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is setting up a CI/CD pipeline for a containerized microservices application hosted on a Kubernetes cluster. They want zero-downtime deployments where traffic shifts gradually from the old version to the new version. Which deployment strategy BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is deploying cloud resources using Terraform and notices that running 'terraform apply' a second time without any code changes results in no infrastructure modifications. Which Terraform characteristic does this BEST illustrate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Immutability"},{"id":"b","text":"Idempotency"},{"id":"c","text":"Scalability"},{"id":"d","text":"Elasticity"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Idempotency means that applying the same operation multiple times produces the same result without unintended side effects. Terraform compares the desired state in configuration files with the current state file and only makes changes when there is a drift. Immutability refers to not modifying existing resources but replacing them. Scalability and elasticity relate to capacity management, not configuration behavior.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/intro/core-workflow","label":"Terraform Core Workflow – HashiCorp Developer"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is deploying cloud resources using Terraform and notices that running 'terraform apply' a second time without any code changes results in no infrastructure modifications. Which Terraform characteristic does this BEST illustrate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An architect is designing the deployment of a highly available web application across multiple cloud regions. The requirement specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of less than 5 minutes. Which deployment pattern BEST satisfies this RTO?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Cold standby with manual failover triggered by the on-call engineer"},{"id":"b","text":"Pilot light with pre-configured core services that scale on demand"},{"id":"c","text":"Active-active multi-region deployment with automated DNS failover"},{"id":"d","text":"Backup and restore from object storage with a recovery script"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An active-active multi-region deployment means both regions are simultaneously serving traffic. Automated DNS failover routes users to the healthy region within seconds, achieving an RTO well under 5 minutes. Cold standby requires manual intervention, making sub-5-minute RTO unlikely. Pilot light still requires scaling up services, which can take several minutes. Backup and restore typically results in RTOs of 30 minutes to hours.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"Disaster Recovery of Workloads on AWS – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An architect is designing the deployment of a highly available web application across multiple cloud regions. The requirement specifies a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of less than 5 minutes. Which deployment pattern BEST satisfies this RTO?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy a new virtual machine image that has been pre-configured with all required software and security hardening. The image should be treated as unchangeable after creation; any updates require deploying a new image. Which concept BEST describes this approach?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Mutable infrastructure"},{"id":"b","text":"Immutable infrastructure"},{"id":"c","text":"Elastic infrastructure"},{"id":"d","text":"Serverless infrastructure"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Immutable infrastructure means that once a server or image is deployed, it is never modified in place. Updates are made by building a new image and replacing the old instance. This approach reduces configuration drift and improves repeatability. Mutable infrastructure allows in-place changes. Elastic infrastructure refers to dynamic scaling. Serverless infrastructure abstracts server management but does not specifically address image mutability.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.hashicorp.com/resources/what-is-mutable-vs-immutable-infrastructure","label":"Immutable Infrastructure – HashiCorp"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy a new virtual machine image that has been pre-configured with all required software and security hardening. The image should be treated as unchangeable after creation; any updates require deploying a new image. Which concept BEST describes this approach?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A team is deploying a containerized application and needs to decide between using a container orchestration platform and deploying containers directly on virtual machines without orchestration. Which benefit is EXCLUSIVELY provided by a container orchestration platform such as Kubernetes?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The ability to run Docker containers"},{"id":"b","text":"Automatic rescheduling of failed containers to healthy nodes"},{"id":"c","text":"The ability to build container images from a Dockerfile"},{"id":"d","text":"Access to a container image registry"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Automatic rescheduling (self-healing) of failed containers to healthy nodes is a core orchestration feature provided by platforms like Kubernetes. Running Docker containers and building images from Dockerfiles can be done without orchestration. Container image registries are independent services (e.g., Docker Hub, Amazon ECR) that can be used with or without orchestration.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/overview/","label":"Kubernetes – What is Kubernetes?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A team is deploying a containerized application and needs to decide between using a container orchestration platform and deploying containers directly on virtual machines without orchestration. Which benefit is EXCLUSIVELY provided by a container orchestration platform such as Kubernetes?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization wants to deploy applications using a Platform as a Service (PaaS) model to reduce operational overhead. Compared to Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), which management responsibility does the cloud customer RETAIN when using PaaS?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Operating system patching and maintenance"},{"id":"b","text":"Hypervisor and physical host management"},{"id":"c","text":"Application code and data"},{"id":"d","text":"Middleware and runtime environment patching"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In a PaaS model, the cloud provider manages the infrastructure, operating system, middleware, and runtime. The customer retains responsibility for the application code and data they deploy on the platform. OS patching, hypervisor management, and middleware/runtime patching are all handled by the provider in PaaS, unlike IaaS where the customer handles OS and above.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/security/fundamentals/shared-responsibility","label":"Shared Responsibility Model – Microsoft Learn"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization wants to deploy applications using a Platform as a Service (PaaS) model to reduce operational overhead. Compared to Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), which management responsibility does the cloud customer RETAIN when using PaaS?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is planning a deployment and needs to choose between horizontal scaling and vertical scaling for a stateless web application that experiences unpredictable traffic spikes. Which option BEST describes the advantage of horizontal scaling in this scenario?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Horizontal scaling increases the CPU and RAM of an existing instance, which is faster than provisioning new instances"},{"id":"b","text":"Horizontal scaling adds more instances to distribute the load, and stateless applications can be served by any instance without session affinity issues"},{"id":"c","text":"Horizontal scaling eliminates the need for a load balancer because each instance independently handles all traffic"},{"id":"d","text":"Horizontal scaling is only suitable for stateful applications because it requires sticky sessions"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Horizontal scaling (scaling out) adds additional instances and distributes traffic via a load balancer. Stateless applications are ideal for this model because any instance can handle any request, eliminating session affinity dependencies. Vertical scaling (scaling up) increases the resources of a single instance, which has upper limits and typically requires downtime. Horizontal scaling requires a load balancer, not eliminates it. Sticky sessions are associated with stateful, not stateless, applications.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/what-is-amazon-ec2-auto-scaling.html","label":"Scaling Cloud Resources – AWS Auto Scaling"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is planning a deployment and needs to choose between horizontal scaling and vertical scaling for a stateless web application that experiences unpredictable traffic spikes. Which option BEST describes the advantage of horizontal scaling in this scenario?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is migrating an on-premises application to the cloud and wants to move the workload with the LEAST amount of re-architecture. The application binaries and configurations will remain unchanged. Which migration strategy BEST describes this approach?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Replatform (lift-and-reshape)"},{"id":"b","text":"Refactor (re-architect)"},{"id":"c","text":"Rehost (lift-and-shift)"},{"id":"d","text":"Repurchase (drop-and-shop)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Rehosting, commonly called lift-and-shift, moves the application to the cloud with minimal or no changes to the application itself. This is the fastest migration path with the least re-architecture. Replatforming makes minor optimizations without changing core architecture. Refactoring involves significant redesign to take advantage of cloud-native features. Repurchasing replaces the application with a SaaS alternative.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/enterprise-strategy/6-strategies-for-migrating-applications-to-the-cloud/","label":"6 Strategies for Migrating Applications to the Cloud – AWS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is migrating an on-premises application to the cloud and wants to move the workload with the LEAST amount of re-architecture. The application binaries and configurations will remain unchanged. Which migration strategy BEST describes this approach?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud deployment pipeline uses a configuration management tool to enforce the desired state of servers after provisioning. An engineer discovers that a server's configuration has drifted from the defined baseline. Which feature of configuration management tools like Ansible or Puppet AUTOMATICALLY corrects this drift?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Ad-hoc command execution"},{"id":"b","text":"Desired state enforcement (continuous remediation)"},{"id":"c","text":"Agentless architecture"},{"id":"d","text":"Role-based access control (RBAC) for playbooks"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Desired state enforcement (also called continuous remediation or convergence) is the feature by which configuration management tools periodically check a node's current state against the defined baseline and automatically correct any drift. Ad-hoc command execution runs one-off commands and does not continuously enforce state. Agentless architecture is a connectivity model, not a drift-correction mechanism. RBAC controls who can run playbooks but does not remediate drift.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.puppet.com/docs/puppet/latest/puppet_index.html","label":"Puppet – How Puppet Works"},{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/getting_started/introduction.html","label":"Ansible – What is Ansible?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud deployment pipeline uses a configuration management tool to enforce the desired state of servers after provisioning. An engineer discovers that a server's configuration has drifted from the defined baseline. Which feature of configuration management tools like Ansible or Puppet AUTOMATICALLY corrects this drift?$patch$);

-- CV0-004-P6: 40 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is designing a multi-tier web application that must remain available during a single availability zone failure. The application currently runs entirely in one availability zone within a single region. Which architectural change BEST addresses this requirement while minimizing cost?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy identical application stacks across two availability zones and use a load balancer to distribute traffic between them."},{"id":"b","text":"Replicate the entire application stack to a second cloud region and use DNS failover to redirect traffic."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the instance sizes of all components within the single availability zone to handle potential load spikes."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable automated snapshots of all instances every 15 minutes to allow rapid recovery after a zone failure."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Deploying across two availability zones (AZs) within the same region with a load balancer provides high availability against a single AZ failure at the lowest incremental cost. AZs are physically separate data centers within a region, so a failure in one does not affect the other. Option B (multi-region) is more expensive and exceeds the stated requirement. Option C (vertical scaling) does nothing to address zone-level failures. Option D (snapshots) reduces data loss but does not prevent downtime during an AZ outage.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-regions-availability-zones.html","label":"AWS – Regions and Availability Zones"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is designing a multi-tier web application that must remain available during a single availability zone failure. The application currently runs entirely in one availability zone within a single region. Which architectural change BEST addresses this requirement while minimizing cost?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization needs a cloud deployment model in which its sensitive workloads remain on dedicated on-premises infrastructure while less-sensitive workloads can burst into a public cloud provider during peak demand. Which deployment model BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Public cloud only, with strict IAM policies to isolate sensitive workloads."},{"id":"b","text":"Community cloud shared with trusted industry partners."},{"id":"c","text":"Hybrid cloud combining on-premises private infrastructure with a public cloud provider."},{"id":"d","text":"Multi-cloud using two separate public cloud providers for redundancy."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A hybrid cloud model connects private (on-premises) infrastructure to a public cloud, allowing sensitive data to remain on-premises while enabling cloud bursting for less-sensitive workloads during demand spikes. Option A (public cloud only) does not satisfy the requirement for dedicated on-premises infrastructure. Option B (community cloud) is shared infrastructure and does not provide dedicated on-premises resources. Option D (multi-cloud) uses multiple public clouds but still lacks the private on-premises component the organization requires.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-145 – The NIST Definition of Cloud Computing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization needs a cloud deployment model in which its sensitive workloads remain on dedicated on-premises infrastructure while less-sensitive workloads can burst into a public cloud provider during peak demand. Which deployment model BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A solutions architect is selecting a storage tier for a cloud-based archival system that stores compliance records accessed on average once per year. The primary design goal is to minimize long-term storage cost. Which storage class or tier is MOST appropriate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"High-performance block storage with SSD-backed volumes."},{"id":"b","text":"Standard object storage with frequent-access retrieval."},{"id":"c","text":"Cold or archive-tier object storage with retrieval times measured in hours."},{"id":"d","text":"In-memory distributed cache storage for rapid retrieval."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cold or archive-tier object storage (e.g., AWS S3 Glacier, Azure Archive, or Google Cloud Archive) is purpose-built for data that is rarely accessed and must be retained for long periods. It offers the lowest per-GB storage cost at the expense of longer retrieval times, which is acceptable for annual compliance access. Option A (SSD block storage) is optimized for high IOPS and carries a premium cost unsuitable for archival. Option B (standard object storage) is more expensive per GB than archive tiers for infrequently accessed data. Option D (in-memory cache) is designed for sub-millisecond access and is the most expensive tier.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/s3/storage-classes/","label":"AWS S3 Storage Classes Overview"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/blobs/access-tiers-overview","label":"Azure Blob Storage Access Tiers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A solutions architect is selecting a storage tier for a cloud-based archival system that stores compliance records accessed on average once per year. The primary design goal is to minimize long-term storage cost. Which storage class or tier is MOST appropriate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During the design phase of a new cloud application, the team must define the Recovery Point Objective (RPO) and Recovery Time Objective (RTO). Which statement CORRECTLY describes the relationship between these two metrics?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"RPO defines the maximum tolerable downtime after a failure, while RTO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time."},{"id":"b","text":"RPO defines the maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time, while RTO defines the maximum tolerable duration to restore service after a failure."},{"id":"c","text":"RPO and RTO are interchangeable terms that both describe acceptable downtime thresholds."},{"id":"d","text":"RTO is always numerically greater than RPO in any well-designed business continuity plan."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$RPO (Recovery Point Objective) measures how much data loss is acceptable, expressed as the maximum age of data that must be recoverable — essentially how far back in time recovery can go. RTO (Recovery Time Objective) measures how quickly services must be restored after a disruption. They are distinct metrics: a system might have an RPO of 1 hour (data backup frequency) but an RTO of 4 hours (time to rebuild and restore). Option A reverses the two definitions. Option C is incorrect — they measure different dimensions. Option D is false; there is no universal rule that RTO > RPO.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-objectives.html","label":"AWS – Disaster Recovery of Workloads on AWS (RPO/RTO)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During the design phase of a new cloud application, the team must define the Recovery Point Objective (RPO) and Recovery Time Objective (RTO). Which statement CORRECTLY describes the relationship between these two metrics?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is designing an application that must automatically add compute instances when CPU utilization exceeds 75% and remove them when utilization drops below 30%. Which cloud capability DIRECTLY enables this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Vertical scaling (scale up/down) triggered by manual operator approval."},{"id":"b","text":"Horizontal autoscaling with policy-based rules tied to a performance metric."},{"id":"c","text":"Reserved instance purchasing to guarantee capacity during peak periods."},{"id":"d","text":"A content delivery network (CDN) to cache responses and reduce backend load."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Horizontal autoscaling automatically adds (scales out) or removes (scales in) compute instances based on defined metric thresholds — in this case CPU utilization. This is the textbook definition of policy-driven horizontal autoscaling. Option A (vertical scaling with manual approval) neither automates the process nor adds new instances. Option C (reserved instances) pre-purchases capacity but does not dynamically add or remove instances. Option D (CDN) reduces origin load by caching content but does not provision or deprovision compute instances.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/autoscale/autoscale-overview","label":"Azure Autoscale Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/what-is-amazon-ec2-auto-scaling.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling – How It Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is designing an application that must automatically add compute instances when CPU utilization exceeds 75% and remove them when utilization drops below 30%. Which cloud capability DIRECTLY enables this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An architect is comparing cloud service models for a new project. The development team wants maximum control over the operating system, middleware, and runtime environment, but does not want to manage physical hardware or the hypervisor layer. Which service model BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Software as a Service (SaaS)"},{"id":"b","text":"Platform as a Service (PaaS)"},{"id":"c","text":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)"},{"id":"d","text":"Function as a Service (FaaS)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$IaaS provides virtualized compute, storage, and networking resources while the cloud provider manages the physical hardware and hypervisor. This gives the customer full control over the OS, middleware, and runtime. PaaS (Option B) abstracts the OS and runtime from the customer, reducing control. SaaS (Option A) delivers fully managed applications with no infrastructure control. FaaS (Option D) abstracts everything except the function code itself, providing the least infrastructure control.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-145 – Cloud Service Models"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/guide/technology-choices/compute-decision-tree","label":"Microsoft Azure – IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An architect is comparing cloud service models for a new project. The development team wants maximum control over the operating system, middleware, and runtime environment, but does not want to manage physical hardware or the hypervisor layer. Which service model BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is designing a cloud architecture using a microservices pattern. Services need to communicate asynchronously so that a failure in one downstream service does not cause cascading failures upstream. Which integration pattern BEST achieves this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Synchronous REST API calls with retry logic and exponential backoff."},{"id":"b","text":"A message queue or message broker enabling producers and consumers to operate independently."},{"id":"c","text":"A shared relational database that all microservices read from and write to directly."},{"id":"d","text":"Remote Procedure Call (RPC) with a timeout of 30 seconds per call."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A message queue or broker (e.g., RabbitMQ, AWS SQS, Azure Service Bus) decouples producers from consumers. The producer places a message on the queue and continues processing regardless of whether the consumer is available. This prevents cascading failures because downstream unavailability does not block upstream services. Option A (synchronous REST with retries) still creates temporal coupling — if the downstream service is unavailable long enough, the upstream service will eventually fail. Option C (shared database) creates tight coupling and is an anti-pattern in microservices. Option D (RPC with timeout) is synchronous and will still cause upstream stalls or failures if the timeout is reached repeatedly.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/welcome.html","label":"AWS SQS – How It Works"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/service-bus-messaging/service-bus-messaging-overview","label":"Azure Service Bus – Messaging Concepts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is designing a cloud architecture using a microservices pattern. Services need to communicate asynchronously so that a failure in one downstream service does not cause cascading failures upstream. Which integration pattern BEST achieves this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect must design a solution that ensures application workloads are distributed across multiple cloud providers to avoid vendor lock-in and increase resilience. Which architectural strategy BEST describes this approach?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Single-cloud architecture with geo-redundant regions from the same provider."},{"id":"b","text":"Multi-cloud architecture that distributes workloads across two or more independent cloud providers."},{"id":"c","text":"Hybrid cloud architecture connecting on-premises infrastructure to one public cloud provider."},{"id":"d","text":"Community cloud architecture shared among organizations in the same regulatory vertical."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A multi-cloud strategy intentionally uses services from two or more distinct cloud providers. This approach avoids vendor lock-in because workloads and data are not tied to a single provider's APIs or proprietary services, and it increases resilience because a provider-wide outage affects only a portion of the total workload. Option A (single-cloud geo-redundancy) improves resilience within one provider but does not address vendor lock-in. Option C (hybrid cloud) adds on-premises infrastructure but uses only one public cloud, which still creates dependency on that vendor. Option D (community cloud) is a sharing model among organizations, not a multi-provider strategy.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/architecture/multicloud-overview","label":"Google Cloud – Multi-cloud Architecture Patterns"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect must design a solution that ensures application workloads are distributed across multiple cloud providers to avoid vendor lock-in and increase resilience. Which architectural strategy BEST describes this approach?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a multi-tier web application on a public cloud provider. The architecture requires that the database tier is not accessible from the internet but must be reachable by the application tier. Which network design best achieves this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Place all tiers in the same public subnet and use host-based firewall rules to restrict database access."},{"id":"b","text":"Place the web tier in a public subnet and the application and database tiers in private subnets, using security groups to allow only application-tier traffic to the database."},{"id":"c","text":"Place all tiers in a private subnet and expose the database directly through a NAT gateway for internet queries."},{"id":"d","text":"Place the database tier in a public subnet with a network ACL that blocks all inbound traffic except port 3306 from any IP."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Placing the web tier in a public subnet and back-end tiers in private subnets is the standard multi-tier network isolation pattern. Security groups (stateful firewalls) can then restrict database port access to only the application tier's security group, ensuring the database is never exposed to the internet. Option A relies solely on host-based firewalls with no network-level segmentation. Option C incorrectly exposes the database through a NAT gateway. Option D places the database in a public subnet, making it internet-routable despite the ACL restriction.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Subnets.html","label":"AWS VPC Subnets and Routing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a multi-tier web application on a public cloud provider. The architecture requires that the database tier is not accessible from the internet but must be reachable by the application tier. Which network design best achieves this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud deployment, an engineer needs to ensure that a newly provisioned virtual machine automatically receives the correct software configuration upon first boot without manual intervention. Which approach is MOST appropriate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Manually SSH into the instance after provisioning and run configuration scripts."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a cloud-init configuration file or user-data script passed at instance launch to automate configuration at first boot."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a static AMI or machine image and manually update it every time a configuration change is required."},{"id":"d","text":"Attach an additional block storage volume containing configuration files and instruct operations staff to mount it after deployment."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cloud-init (or equivalent user-data mechanisms) is the industry-standard approach for bootstrapping cloud instances automatically at first boot. It can install packages, write files, and run scripts without human intervention. Option A requires manual SSH access, defeating the purpose of automation. Option C creates an immutable image but does not handle dynamic, first-boot configuration without rebuilding the image for every change. Option D still requires manual post-deployment steps.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://cloudinit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/","label":"cloud-init Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/user-data.html","label":"AWS EC2 User Data"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud deployment, an engineer needs to ensure that a newly provisioned virtual machine automatically receives the correct software configuration upon first boot without manual intervention. Which approach is MOST appropriate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants to deploy infrastructure across multiple cloud regions using a repeatable, version-controlled method to avoid configuration drift. Which practice BEST fulfills this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use the cloud provider's web console to manually configure resources in each region, then document the steps in a wiki."},{"id":"b","text":"Write shell scripts that call the cloud CLI and store them in a shared folder on a file server."},{"id":"c","text":"Use an Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tool such as Terraform or AWS CloudFormation with templates stored in a version-control system."},{"id":"d","text":"Take periodic snapshots of each resource's configuration and store them in object storage."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tools allow infrastructure to be defined in declarative or imperative templates that can be stored in version control, reviewed via pull requests, and applied consistently across regions, eliminating configuration drift. Option A is manual and not repeatable at scale. Option B uses scripts but lacks the state management and declarative idempotency of dedicated IaC tools. Option D captures state snapshots but does not provide a mechanism to reproduce or enforce configuration.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/docs","label":"HashiCorp Terraform Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/Welcome.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation User Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants to deploy infrastructure across multiple cloud regions using a repeatable, version-controlled method to avoid configuration drift. Which practice BEST fulfills this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team needs to release a new application version to production while ensuring that they can instantly revert to the previous version if a critical issue is detected. Which deployment strategy BEST meets this need?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Rolling deployment, updating instances one at a time until all are on the new version."},{"id":"b","text":"Blue/green deployment, keeping the old environment running and switching traffic to the new environment only after validation."},{"id":"c","text":"In-place deployment, stopping all instances and replacing the application binary simultaneously."},{"id":"d","text":"Canary deployment, routing 100% of traffic to the new version immediately after release."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Blue/green deployment maintains two identical environments. Traffic is switched to the new (green) environment only after it is validated. If an issue is found, traffic is simply switched back to the old (blue) environment for an instant rollback. Rolling deployments reduce downtime but make full rollback complex once many instances are updated. In-place deployments have no fallback environment. A canary deployment routes only a small percentage of traffic initially, not 100%, and provides gradual rollout rather than instant rollback.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/overview-deployment-options/bluegreen-deployments.html","label":"AWS Blue/Green Deployments"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team needs to release a new application version to production while ensuring that they can instantly revert to the previous version if a critical issue is detected. Which deployment strategy BEST meets this need?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is designing an auto-scaling group for a stateless web application. The team wants to ensure new instances are ready to serve traffic within two minutes of a scale-out event. Which technique MOST directly reduces instance launch and readiness time?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use a base OS image and install all application dependencies via a long user-data script at each launch."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a pre-baked golden image (custom AMI or machine image) that already contains the application and dependencies."},{"id":"c","text":"Use a larger instance type so software installation finishes faster."},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the auto-scaling cooldown period to give instances more time to complete installations."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Pre-baked golden images contain all required software pre-installed and pre-configured, so instances boot and are immediately ready to serve traffic, drastically reducing launch time. Option A relies on installing software at launch, which takes significant time. Option C uses a larger instance type but does not reduce the software installation steps. Option D increases the cooldown period, which only delays the next scale action and does not make individual instances ready faster.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/AMIs.html","label":"AWS EC2 AMI Best Practices"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/linux/tutorial-custom-images","label":"Azure VM Custom Images"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is designing an auto-scaling group for a stateless web application. The team wants to ensure new instances are ready to serve traffic within two minutes of a scale-out event. Which technique MOST directly reduces instance launch and readiness time?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A development team uses a CI/CD pipeline and needs to store sensitive database credentials required during the deployment stage. Storing them in plain text in the pipeline configuration file is not acceptable. What is the BEST approach?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Encode the credentials in Base64 and store them as a pipeline environment variable."},{"id":"b","text":"Hard-code the credentials directly in the application's source code repository."},{"id":"c","text":"Store the credentials in a secrets management service such as HashiCorp Vault or a cloud-native secrets manager and inject them at runtime."},{"id":"d","text":"Email the credentials to the deployment team before each release so they can enter them manually."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Secrets management services encrypt credentials at rest and in transit, enforce access controls, support rotation, and inject secrets at runtime without ever writing them to disk or storing them in source code. Base64 encoding (Option A) is not encryption and provides no real security. Hard-coding in source code (Option B) is a serious security anti-pattern. Manual email distribution (Option D) is insecure and not scalable. Dedicated secrets managers are the industry best practice.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/vault/docs","label":"HashiCorp Vault Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/intro.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager User Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A development team uses a CI/CD pipeline and needs to store sensitive database credentials required during the deployment stage. Storing them in plain text in the pipeline configuration file is not acceptable. What is the BEST approach?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is deploying a containerized microservices application and needs a platform that automates container scheduling, self-healing, and horizontal scaling. Which technology is MOST appropriate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Docker Compose running on a single virtual machine."},{"id":"b","text":"A container registry such as Amazon ECR or Docker Hub."},{"id":"c","text":"A container orchestration platform such as Kubernetes."},{"id":"d","text":"A static VM provisioned with Docker Engine only."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Kubernetes is a container orchestration platform that provides automated scheduling, self-healing (restarting failed containers), and horizontal pod autoscaling across a cluster of nodes. Docker Compose (Option A) is designed for single-host multi-container applications and lacks cluster-level orchestration. A container registry (Option B) stores container images but does not run or orchestrate them. A single VM with Docker Engine (Option D) provides no orchestration, auto-scaling, or self-healing across multiple hosts.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/home/","label":"Kubernetes Official Documentation"},{"url":"https://landscape.cncf.io/","label":"CNCF Cloud Native Landscape"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is deploying a containerized microservices application and needs a platform that automates container scheduling, self-healing, and horizontal scaling. Which technology is MOST appropriate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During cloud resource deployment, a team wants to ensure that a CloudFormation stack does not deploy if a required S3 bucket name parameter is left blank. Which CloudFormation feature BEST enforces this validation at deploy time?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use a CloudFormation Output to display the parameter value after deployment."},{"id":"b","text":"Add an AllowedPattern or MinLength constraint to the parameter definition in the template."},{"id":"c","text":"Add a CloudFormation Mapping that provides default values for all parameters."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a separate Lambda function that checks parameters after the stack is deployed."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$CloudFormation parameter constraints such as AllowedPattern, MinLength, MaxLength, AllowedValues, and MinValue/MaxValue are evaluated before stack creation begins. If a constraint is violated, the deployment is rejected immediately. Outputs (Option A) only surface values after deployment, not before. Mappings (Option C) provide lookup values but do not validate user-supplied parameters. A post-deployment Lambda (Option D) checks after the fact, meaning invalid stacks could be partially created before detection.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/parameters-section-structure.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation Parameters"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During cloud resource deployment, a team wants to ensure that a CloudFormation stack does not deploy if a required S3 bucket name parameter is left blank. Which CloudFormation feature BEST enforces this validation at deploy time?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is migrating a legacy on-premises application to the cloud using a lift-and-shift strategy. Which characteristic BEST describes a lift-and-shift migration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Rewriting the application as cloud-native microservices to take full advantage of managed cloud services."},{"id":"b","text":"Moving the application to the cloud with minimal or no changes to the application's code or architecture."},{"id":"c","text":"Decomposing the monolithic application into serverless functions before migration."},{"id":"d","text":"Replacing the existing application with a SaaS product that provides equivalent functionality."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Lift-and-shift (also called rehosting) involves moving an application to the cloud as-is, with little or no modification to its code, architecture, or configuration. It is the fastest migration strategy but does not leverage cloud-native features. Option A describes rearchitecting or re-platforming. Option C describes refactoring toward serverless. Option D describes replacing the application entirely, which is a different migration strategy (repurchase).$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/prescriptive-guidance/latest/migration-replatforming-shift-eft/overview.html","label":"AWS 7 Rs Migration Strategies"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cloud-adoption-framework/adopt/migrate","label":"Azure Cloud Migration Strategies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is migrating a legacy on-premises application to the cloud using a lift-and-shift strategy. Which characteristic BEST describes a lift-and-shift migration?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud deployment pipeline currently deploys directly to production after passing unit tests. The security team requires that all infrastructure changes go through an approval gate before reaching production. Which CI/CD pipeline enhancement addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a parallel unit test stage so tests run faster, reducing overall pipeline time."},{"id":"b","text":"Insert a manual approval step between the staging and production deployment stages."},{"id":"c","text":"Remove the staging environment to streamline the pipeline."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure the pipeline to automatically retry failed deployments without notification."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A manual approval gate (approval step) pauses the pipeline and requires an authorized person to review and approve the change before it proceeds to production. This is the standard method for enforcing human oversight of production changes in a CI/CD pipeline. Option A speeds up testing but adds no approval control. Option C removes a valuable pre-production validation environment. Option D enables silent retries, which can mask failures and bypasses human review.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codepipeline/latest/userguide/approvals.html","label":"AWS CodePipeline Manual Approval Actions"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/pipelines/release/approvals/approvals","label":"Azure DevOps Approval Gates"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud deployment pipeline currently deploys directly to production after passing unit tests. The security team requires that all infrastructure changes go through an approval gate before reaching production. Which CI/CD pipeline enhancement addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is using Terraform to manage cloud infrastructure. After modifying a resource definition, which Terraform command should be run FIRST to preview what changes will be made before applying them?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"terraform apply"},{"id":"b","text":"terraform destroy"},{"id":"c","text":"terraform plan"},{"id":"d","text":"terraform import"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$terraform plan generates an execution plan showing exactly which resources will be created, modified, or destroyed without making any changes to the actual infrastructure. It is the recommended first step before terraform apply. terraform apply (Option A) makes actual changes to infrastructure. terraform destroy (Option B) tears down all managed resources. terraform import (Option D) brings existing resources under Terraform management but does not preview changes.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/commands/plan","label":"Terraform Plan Command"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is using Terraform to manage cloud infrastructure. After modifying a resource definition, which Terraform command should be run FIRST to preview what changes will be made before applying them?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A team is deploying a serverless application using AWS Lambda. They need to ensure that a previous stable version of the Lambda function can be instantly invoked if the newest deployment introduces a regression. Which Lambda feature BEST supports this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Lambda layers, which allow shared libraries to be attached to multiple functions."},{"id":"b","text":"Lambda aliases pointed at specific published function versions, enabling instant traffic routing to a previous version."},{"id":"c","text":"Lambda environment variables, which store configuration values for the function."},{"id":"d","text":"Lambda reserved concurrency, which limits the maximum number of concurrent executions."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Lambda versions are immutable snapshots of a function's code and configuration. Aliases are pointers to specific versions. By updating an alias to point to a previous version, teams can instantly roll back without redeployment. Lambda layers (Option A) share code libraries but do not manage deployment versions. Environment variables (Option C) store configuration but do not enable version rollback. Reserved concurrency (Option D) controls scaling limits, not version management.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/configuration-versions.html","label":"AWS Lambda Function Versions and Aliases"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A team is deploying a serverless application using AWS Lambda. They need to ensure that a previous stable version of the Lambda function can be instantly invoked if the newest deployment introduces a regression. Which Lambda feature BEST supports this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization is deploying a new cloud environment and must ensure all resource provisioning complies with corporate tagging policies before resources are created. Which cloud-native mechanism enforces tagging compliance at deployment time?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Post-deployment cost allocation reports that identify untagged resources."},{"id":"b","text":"A cloud policy engine such as AWS Service Control Policies (SCPs) or Azure Policy that denies resource creation when required tags are absent."},{"id":"c","text":"A weekly automated script that adds default tags to any untagged resources it finds."},{"id":"d","text":"Sending email alerts to the cloud administrator when an untagged resource is detected."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Policy engines like AWS Service Control Policies, AWS Config with auto-remediation, or Azure Policy can evaluate resource requests at the control plane level and deny creation if required tags are missing. This enforces compliance proactively before resources exist. Cost allocation reports (Option A) are reactive and occur after resources are already deployed. A weekly cleanup script (Option C) is reactive and creates a window of non-compliance. Email alerts (Option D) are also reactive and rely on manual remediation.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_manage_policies_scps.html","label":"AWS Service Control Policies"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/governance/policy/overview","label":"Azure Policy Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization is deploying a new cloud environment and must ensure all resource provisioning complies with corporate tagging policies before resources are created. Which cloud-native mechanism enforces tagging compliance at deployment time?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy an application that requires a consistent, low-latency connection between an on-premises data center and the cloud provider. The current internet-based VPN connection has unpredictable latency. Which connectivity option BEST resolves this issue?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the VPN tunnel bandwidth by upgrading to a higher-tier internet service provider plan."},{"id":"b","text":"Establish a dedicated private network connection such as AWS Direct Connect or Azure ExpressRoute between the data center and the cloud."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy a content delivery network (CDN) to cache application data closer to the on-premises location."},{"id":"d","text":"Implement a load balancer in the cloud to distribute traffic across multiple VPN tunnels."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Dedicated private connectivity services like AWS Direct Connect and Azure ExpressRoute provide a physical, dedicated circuit between an on-premises facility and the cloud provider, bypassing the public internet entirely. This delivers consistent, low-latency, and high-bandwidth connectivity. Increasing internet bandwidth (Option A) does not eliminate the inherent variability of the public internet. A CDN (Option C) is designed for content delivery to end users, not for stable hybrid connectivity. Multiple VPN tunnels with a load balancer (Option D) still traverse the public internet, so latency remains unpredictable.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/directconnect/latest/UserGuide/Welcome.html","label":"AWS Direct Connect"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/expressroute/expressroute-introduction","label":"Azure ExpressRoute Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy an application that requires a consistent, low-latency connection between an on-premises data center and the cloud provider. The current internet-based VPN connection has unpredictable latency. Which connectivity option BEST resolves this issue?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations team receives alerts that a production workload's CPU utilization has been consistently above 85% for the past 30 minutes. The team wants to implement an automated response that adds capacity without manual intervention. Which cloud capability BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Vertical scaling triggered by a manual change request"},{"id":"b","text":"Horizontal auto-scaling based on a CloudWatch-style metric alarm threshold"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploying an additional region to distribute the load geographically"},{"id":"d","text":"Increasing the reserved instance count during the next maintenance window"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Horizontal auto-scaling (scaling out) automatically adds compute instances when a defined metric threshold—such as CPU utilization exceeding 85%—is breached, without manual intervention. Vertical scaling (option A) typically requires a restart and is manual. Adding a region (option C) addresses geographic distribution, not rapid automated capacity response. Modifying reserved instances (option D) is a purchasing/planning action, not an automated operational response.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/what-is-amazon-ec2-auto-scaling.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling – How Auto Scaling Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations team receives alerts that a production workload's CPU utilization has been consistently above 85% for the past 30 minutes. The team wants to implement an automated response that adds capacity without manual intervention. Which cloud capability BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations engineer needs to ensure that all activity performed by privileged administrators on cloud infrastructure is recorded and tamper-evident for compliance purposes. Which solution BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enabling verbose application logging on each virtual machine"},{"id":"b","text":"Configuring a cloud-native audit trail service (e.g., AWS CloudTrail or Azure Activity Log) to write immutable logs to a dedicated, write-protected storage bucket"},{"id":"c","text":"Reviewing firewall flow logs on a weekly basis"},{"id":"d","text":"Requiring administrators to submit change tickets before making any changes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Cloud-native audit trail services record API-level management plane activity and, when logs are sent to a write-protected (object-locked) storage bucket, provide tamper-evident records suitable for compliance. Application logging (option A) captures workload events, not privileged infrastructure actions. Firewall flow logs (option C) record network traffic, not admin actions. Change tickets (option D) are a process control, not a technical audit mechanism.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-user-guide.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail – What Is AWS CloudTrail?"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/essentials/activity-log","label":"Azure Monitor Activity Log Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations engineer needs to ensure that all activity performed by privileged administrators on cloud infrastructure is recorded and tamper-evident for compliance purposes. Which solution BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's RTO (Recovery Time Objective) for a critical cloud workload is 1 hour and the RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is 15 minutes. Which backup and recovery strategy BEST satisfies both objectives?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Daily full backups stored in cold archive storage with manual restoration procedures"},{"id":"b","text":"Continuous database replication to a standby in a secondary region with automated failover scripts and hourly snapshots"},{"id":"c","text":"Incremental backups every 30 minutes stored in the same region with no tested restoration procedure"},{"id":"d","text":"Weekly full backups with point-in-time recovery enabled, stored offsite on tape"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Continuous replication keeps data loss below 15 minutes (meeting the RPO), while automated failover scripts can bring the workload online within 1 hour (meeting the RTO). Daily cold-archive backups (option A) cannot meet a 1-hour RTO or 15-minute RPO. Incremental backups every 30 minutes (option C) exceed the RPO and lack a tested restore procedure. Weekly backups on tape (option D) cannot meet either objective.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS Disaster Recovery – RPO and RTO"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's RTO (Recovery Time Objective) for a critical cloud workload is 1 hour and the RPO (Recovery Point Objective) is 15 minutes. Which backup and recovery strategy BEST satisfies both objectives?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team wants to track resource utilization trends over time to make informed decisions about right-sizing virtual machines. Which operational practice BEST supports this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enabling performance monitoring with long-term metric retention and reviewing utilization baselines monthly"},{"id":"b","text":"Increasing all VM sizes by one tier proactively to prevent future bottlenecks"},{"id":"c","text":"Migrating all workloads to containers to eliminate the VM right-sizing concern"},{"id":"d","text":"Reviewing billing invoices at the end of each fiscal quarter"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Collecting performance metrics over time and reviewing utilization baselines allows teams to identify over-provisioned or under-provisioned resources and make data-driven right-sizing decisions. Proactively upsizing all VMs (option B) increases costs without evidence of need. Migrating to containers (option C) changes the architecture but does not inherently solve resource-sizing decisions. Reviewing billing invoices (option D) provides cost data but not the granular utilization data needed for right-sizing.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/essentials/data-platform-metrics","label":"Azure Monitor Metrics Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/compute-optimizer/latest/ug/what-is-compute-optimizer.html","label":"AWS Compute Optimizer – Right Sizing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team wants to track resource utilization trends over time to make informed decisions about right-sizing virtual machines. Which operational practice BEST supports this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a post-incident review, the team discovers that an outage lasted longer than necessary because engineers did not follow a documented runbook. Which process improvement BEST reduces the likelihood of this occurring in a future incident?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Decommission all undocumented services"},{"id":"b","text":"Mandate runbook review and tabletop exercises for on-call engineers on a recurring schedule"},{"id":"c","text":"Purchase additional monitoring tooling to detect incidents faster"},{"id":"d","text":"Require all engineers to obtain a new certification before joining the on-call rotation"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Regular runbook reviews and tabletop exercises ensure that on-call engineers are familiar with documented procedures before an incident occurs, reducing response time. Decommissioning undocumented services (option A) addresses documentation gaps but not engineer readiness. Additional monitoring (option C) improves detection but not response execution. Requiring certifications (option D) builds general knowledge but does not address familiarity with organization-specific runbooks.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://sre.google/sre-book/managing-incidents/","label":"Google SRE Book – Incident Management"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a post-incident review, the team discovers that an outage lasted longer than necessary because engineers did not follow a documented runbook. Which process improvement BEST reduces the likelihood of this occurring in a future incident?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator needs to apply OS patches to a fleet of 200 Linux virtual machines within a defined maintenance window while ensuring zero-downtime for the application. Which approach BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Patch all 200 VMs simultaneously during off-peak hours"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a rolling update strategy, patching a subset of VMs at a time, with load-balancer health checks confirming availability before continuing"},{"id":"c","text":"Take a snapshot of each VM, patch in place, and restore from snapshot if errors occur, for all VMs at once"},{"id":"d","text":"Notify users of a scheduled maintenance window and patch all VMs with the application offline"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A rolling update patches a small batch of VMs at a time while the remaining VMs continue serving traffic; load-balancer health checks prevent traffic from being routed to unavailable instances. Patching all VMs simultaneously (option A) eliminates redundancy and risks full application downtime. Simultaneously snapshotting and patching all VMs (option C) still causes a service disruption if errors occur. Taking the application fully offline (option D) directly violates the zero-downtime requirement.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-patch.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/update-manager/overview","label":"Azure Update Manager Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator needs to apply OS patches to a fleet of 200 Linux virtual machines within a defined maintenance window while ensuring zero-downtime for the application. Which approach BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization is implementing a tagging strategy across all cloud resources. Which benefit does a well-enforced tagging policy PRIMARILY provide to operations teams?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"It automatically scales resources based on tag values"},{"id":"b","text":"It enables cost allocation, resource ownership identification, and automated policy enforcement across the environment"},{"id":"c","text":"It encrypts data at rest for all tagged resources"},{"id":"d","text":"It eliminates the need for access control policies by grouping resources logically"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A well-enforced tagging policy allows teams to attribute costs to business units, quickly identify resource owners, and apply automated governance policies (such as shutting down untagged resources). Tags do not trigger auto-scaling (option A), provide encryption (option C), or replace access control policies (option D); those are separate cloud capabilities.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/tag-editor/latest/userguide/best-practices-and-strats.html","label":"AWS Tagging Best Practices"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cloud-adoption-framework/ready/azure-best-practices/resource-tagging","label":"Azure Resource Tagging – Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization is implementing a tagging strategy across all cloud resources. Which benefit does a well-enforced tagging policy PRIMARILY provide to operations teams?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A SaaS application hosted in the cloud is experiencing intermittent latency spikes. The operations team wants to identify whether the issue originates at the application layer, the database layer, or the network layer. Which monitoring approach is MOST effective for isolating the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Review only end-user response-time metrics from the load balancer access logs"},{"id":"b","text":"Implement distributed tracing across all service components to correlate request latency with specific layers"},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the VM size for both the application servers and database servers simultaneously"},{"id":"d","text":"Restart all services during a maintenance window and monitor whether latency spikes recur"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Distributed tracing follows a request through every service and infrastructure layer, producing a trace with timing breakdowns per component. This allows the team to pinpoint whether latency is introduced at the application, database, or network layer. Load balancer logs alone (option A) only show aggregate response times without per-layer detail. Resizing VMs (option C) may change behavior but does not identify the root cause. Restarting services (option D) might temporarily resolve the issue but provides no root-cause data.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/xray/latest/devguide/aws-xray.html","label":"AWS X-Ray – Distributed Tracing"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/app/distributed-tracing-telemetry-correlation","label":"Azure Application Insights Distributed Tracing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A SaaS application hosted in the cloud is experiencing intermittent latency spikes. The operations team wants to identify whether the issue originates at the application layer, the database layer, or the network layer. Which monitoring approach is MOST effective for isolating the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization must demonstrate that its cloud environment meets a specific regulatory compliance framework on an ongoing basis. Which operational practice BEST supports continuous compliance validation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Conducting a single annual penetration test and storing the report for auditors"},{"id":"b","text":"Implementing a cloud security posture management (CSPM) tool that continuously evaluates resources against compliance benchmarks and generates real-time findings"},{"id":"c","text":"Requiring developers to self-certify compliance before each deployment"},{"id":"d","text":"Purchasing a compliance attestation letter from the cloud service provider"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A CSPM tool continuously scans cloud resources and configurations against regulatory benchmarks (e.g., CIS, PCI-DSS, HIPAA) and provides real-time findings, enabling ongoing compliance validation. An annual pen test (option A) is a point-in-time assessment. Developer self-certification (option C) is a manual, error-prone process. A CSP attestation letter (option D) covers the provider's infrastructure, not the customer's workload configuration.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/defender-for-cloud/concept-cloud-security-posture-management","label":"Microsoft Defender for Cloud – CSPM Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/what-is-securityhub.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Compliance Checks"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization must demonstrate that its cloud environment meets a specific regulatory compliance framework on an ongoing basis. Which operational practice BEST supports continuous compliance validation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations team has been tasked with reducing infrastructure costs without degrading application performance. After reviewing utilization reports, they find that several virtual machines are running at less than 10% CPU and 15% memory utilization consistently over 90 days. What is the MOST operationally appropriate action?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Migrate the underutilized VMs to a larger instance type to add headroom for future growth"},{"id":"b","text":"Downsize the underutilized VMs to a smaller instance type that aligns with observed utilization patterns, after validating the change in a staging environment"},{"id":"c","text":"Immediately terminate the underutilized VMs without further analysis"},{"id":"d","text":"Leave the VMs unchanged because low utilization indicates healthy headroom"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Downsizing underutilized resources to a smaller instance type directly reduces costs while maintaining performance, as actual utilization is well below capacity. Validating in a staging environment first mitigates risk. Upsizing (option A) would increase costs unnecessarily. Immediate termination (option C) without analysis risks removing instances that serve a purpose not visible in CPU/memory metrics alone. Leaving VMs unchanged (option D) ignores the cost-optimization opportunity.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/compute-optimizer/latest/ug/view-ec2-recommendations.html","label":"AWS Compute Optimizer – Rightsizing Recommendations"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/instances/apply-machine-type-recommendations-for-instances","label":"Google Cloud – VM Rightsizing Recommendations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations team has been tasked with reducing infrastructure costs without degrading application performance. After reviewing utilization reports, they find that several virtual machines are running at less than 10% CPU and 15% memory utilization consistently over 90 days. What is the MOST operationally appropriate action?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud security engineer is reviewing the architecture of a multi-tenant SaaS application hosted on a public cloud provider. The application stores sensitive customer data, and the engineer must ensure that one tenant cannot access another tenant's data even if they share the same underlying compute instance. Which security control BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Implement network segmentation using separate Virtual Private Clouds (VPCs) for each tenant"},{"id":"b","text":"Enforce data-level isolation through tenant-specific encryption keys managed in a dedicated key management service (KMS)"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy a Web Application Firewall (WAF) in front of the application to filter malicious tenant requests"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable multi-factor authentication (MFA) for all tenant administrator accounts"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In a multi-tenant environment where tenants share the same underlying compute instance, network segmentation (option A) alone does not prevent data-level access between tenants on the same host. The most effective control in this scenario is enforcing data-level isolation using tenant-specific encryption keys stored and managed in a dedicated Key Management Service (KMS). Even if one tenant's process could somehow access another tenant's data at rest, the data would remain unintelligible without the correct tenant-specific key. Option A (VPC separation) is a valid network isolation control but does not address the threat when compute is shared at the instance level. Option C (WAF) protects against web-layer attacks such as SQL injection or XSS but does not enforce data isolation between tenants. Option D (MFA) strengthens authentication but does not prevent data leakage between tenants at the storage or compute layer.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives – Security Domain"},{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-204/final","label":"NIST SP 800-204 – Security Strategies for Microservices and Multi-Tenant Architectures"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/concepts.html","label":"AWS Key Management Service – Multi-Tenant Data Isolation"},{"url":"https://cloudsecurityalliance.org/research/guidance/","label":"CSA – Security Guidance for Critical Areas of Focus in Cloud Computing v4.0"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud security engineer is reviewing the architecture of a multi-tenant SaaS application hosted on a public cloud provider. The application stores sensitive customer data, and the engineer must ensure that one tenant cannot access another tenant's data even if they share the same underlying compute instance. Which security control BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator notices that an application hosted on a virtual machine in a public cloud environment is intermittently dropping user connections. CPU and memory utilization appear normal. Network throughput logs show periodic spikes reaching the instance's bandwidth cap. Which troubleshooting step should the administrator perform FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the virtual machine's vCPU count to handle more concurrent connections"},{"id":"b","text":"Review network flow logs to identify the source and pattern of the bandwidth spikes"},{"id":"c","text":"Immediately migrate the workload to a larger instance type"},{"id":"d","text":"Disable all non-essential services running on the virtual machine"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When diagnosing intermittent connectivity issues, following a structured troubleshooting methodology means gathering more data before making changes. Reviewing network flow logs reveals whether the spikes are caused by a specific source IP, a scheduled job, a DDoS pattern, or legitimate traffic growth — all of which lead to different remediation paths. Increasing vCPUs (a) does not address a network bandwidth constraint. Migrating to a larger instance (c) may eventually be correct but skips root-cause analysis. Disabling services (d) is disruptive and premature without evidence that a specific service is responsible.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/flow-logs.html","label":"AWS VPC Flow Logs Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator notices that an application hosted on a virtual machine in a public cloud environment is intermittently dropping user connections. CPU and memory utilization appear normal. Network throughput logs show periodic spikes reaching the instance's bandwidth cap. Which troubleshooting step should the administrator perform FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer deploys a containerized microservice to a Kubernetes cluster. The pods start successfully but immediately enter a CrashLoopBackOff state. Which command should the engineer run FIRST to identify the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl delete pod <pod-name> and redeploy the manifest"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl describe pod <pod-name> to view events and container exit reasons"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl scale deployment <deployment-name> --replicas=0 then scale back up"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl apply --force -f deployment.yaml to force a fresh rollout"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$CrashLoopBackOff indicates a container exits immediately after starting. Running 'kubectl describe pod' surfaces the Events section, exit codes, OOMKilled flags, liveness probe failures, and image pull errors — all critical root-cause indicators. Deleting and redeploying (a) does not gather diagnostic information and will reproduce the same error. Scaling to zero and back (c) is equally uninformative. Using --force (d) is dangerous in production and still does not reveal why the container is crashing.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-application/debug-running-pod/","label":"Kubernetes – Debug Running Pods"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer deploys a containerized microservice to a Kubernetes cluster. The pods start successfully but immediately enter a CrashLoopBackOff state. Which command should the engineer run FIRST to identify the root cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$Users in a branch office report that they cannot reach a SaaS application hosted in the cloud, while users at headquarters have no issues. The branch office shares the same DNS server as headquarters. A network trace from the branch office shows that TCP SYN packets to the SaaS application's IP address receive no response. Which component is the MOST likely cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The SaaS provider's application server is down"},{"id":"b","text":"The DNS server is returning incorrect records for the SaaS application"},{"id":"c","text":"A firewall or ACL between the branch office and the internet is blocking outbound traffic to the SaaS application"},{"id":"d","text":"The branch office's DHCP scope has been exhausted"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$TCP SYN packets that receive no response (no SYN-ACK, no RST) indicate the packets are being silently dropped, which is characteristic of a firewall or ACL blocking the traffic. Because headquarters users are unaffected, the SaaS service itself is operational, ruling out (a). DNS is shared and resolves correctly for both sites, ruling out (b). A DHCP exhaustion (d) would prevent the branch office from obtaining IP addresses entirely, not just block a single destination.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-network/network-security-groups-overview","label":"Microsoft Azure Network Security Group Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$Users in a branch office report that they cannot reach a SaaS application hosted in the cloud, while users at headquarters have no issues. The branch office shares the same DNS server as headquarters. A network trace from the branch office shows that TCP SYN packets to the SaaS application's IP address receive no response. Which component is the MOST likely cause?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting slow performance on a cloud-hosted database. Query execution times have increased by 400% over the past week even though query volume is unchanged. Storage I/O metrics show read latency has increased from 2 ms to 35 ms. Which issue is MOST likely responsible?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The database instance's vCPU is throttled due to a burstable instance credit exhaustion"},{"id":"b","text":"The underlying storage volume is experiencing degraded throughput, possibly due to noisy-neighbor contention or a failing disk subsystem"},{"id":"c","text":"The application connection pool is misconfigured and holding idle connections"},{"id":"d","text":"The cloud provider's DNS resolver is introducing lookup latency for each query"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A dramatic increase in storage read latency (2 ms to 35 ms) directly correlates with slower query execution because database reads must wait for I/O to complete. This pattern points to a storage-layer problem such as noisy-neighbor I/O contention on a shared storage tier or a degraded volume. CPU throttling (a) would manifest as high CPU wait times, not elevated read latency. Connection pool misconfiguration (c) would show up as connection queue depth issues, not I/O latency. DNS (d) is irrelevant to intra-query execution time after a connection is established.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/ebs-io-characteristics.html","label":"AWS EBS Volume Performance – Monitoring I/O"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An administrator is troubleshooting slow performance on a cloud-hosted database. Query execution times have increased by 400% over the past week even though query volume is unchanged. Storage I/O metrics show read latency has increased from 2 ms to 35 ms. Which issue is MOST likely responsible?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer receives alerts that an auto-scaling group has launched the maximum number of instances but the application's response time remains unacceptable. CloudWatch metrics show CPU utilization across all instances is only 15%. Which condition is MOST likely preventing the auto-scaling from improving performance?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The auto-scaling policy is configured to scale on CPU utilization, but the actual bottleneck is a downstream dependency such as an overloaded database or external API"},{"id":"b","text":"The instances are launching in the wrong Availability Zone"},{"id":"c","text":"The AMI used for auto-scaling is outdated and contains a misconfigured application"},{"id":"d","text":"The load balancer health checks are failing, causing all new instances to be deregistered"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When CPU is low but latency is high, adding more compute does not resolve the problem because the bottleneck lies elsewhere. A common root cause is a downstream resource — such as a database connection pool limit, an external API rate limit, or a shared cache — that becomes the true constraint regardless of how many application servers are running. Incorrect Availability Zone placement (b) would be flagged by subnet/AZ errors in the scaling activity log. An outdated AMI (c) would typically result in application errors or crashes, not uniform low CPU with high latency. If health checks were failing and instances were deregistered (d), the instance count shown in the scaling group would not appear at maximum.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ts-as-healthchecks.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling – Monitoring and Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer receives alerts that an auto-scaling group has launched the maximum number of instances but the application's response time remains unacceptable. CloudWatch metrics show CPU utilization across all instances is only 15%. Which condition is MOST likely preventing the auto-scaling from improving performance?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After a planned maintenance window, a cloud-hosted web application returns HTTP 502 Bad Gateway errors for all requests. The virtual machines backing the application are running and show no CPU or memory alerts. The load balancer access logs show that it is forwarding requests to the backend instances, but the instances are not returning valid HTTP responses. Which step should the administrator take FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Replace the SSL/TLS certificate on the load balancer"},{"id":"b","text":"Check whether the application service or web server process is running on the backend instances"},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the load balancer's idle timeout setting"},{"id":"d","text":"Reboot all backend instances simultaneously to apply the maintenance changes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$HTTP 502 from a load balancer means the load balancer successfully connected to the backend but received an invalid or no response, which strongly suggests the application process (e.g., Apache, Nginx, Tomcat) is not running or is listening on the wrong port after the maintenance window. Verifying the application service status is the fastest and most targeted first step. SSL certificate issues (a) would typically surface as SSL handshake errors, not 502s. Idle timeout tuning (c) addresses long-running requests, not an immediate total failure. Rebooting all instances simultaneously (d) is disruptive and premature without confirming the root cause.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://repost.aws/knowledge-center/elb-alb-troubleshoot-502-errors","label":"AWS Elastic Load Balancing – Troubleshooting HTTP 502 Errors"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After a planned maintenance window, a cloud-hosted web application returns HTTP 502 Bad Gateway errors for all requests. The virtual machines backing the application are running and show no CPU or memory alerts. The load balancer access logs show that it is forwarding requests to the backend instances, but the instances are not returning valid HTTP responses. Which step should the administrator take FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security operations team notices that object storage buckets in their cloud environment are generating unusually high egress charges even though no new application features have been deployed. Access logs for the buckets are enabled. Which troubleshooting action will MOST efficiently identify the cause of the unexpected egress?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately enable server-side encryption on all buckets to prevent data exfiltration"},{"id":"b","text":"Analyze the bucket access logs to identify which IP addresses, user agents, and IAM principals are responsible for the high-volume GET requests driving egress"},{"id":"c","text":"Delete and recreate the storage buckets with stricter default ACLs"},{"id":"d","text":"Contact the cloud provider's billing support team and wait for their investigation"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Unexpected egress on object storage is most efficiently investigated by examining access logs, which record the requester's IP, IAM principal, request type, bytes transferred, and HTTP status. This allows the team to pinpoint whether the egress is from a misconfigured application, a publicly accessible bucket being scraped, or a compromised credential performing data exfiltration. Enabling encryption (a) does not stop egress and does not identify its source. Deleting and recreating buckets (c) is destructive and destroys the existing logs needed for investigation. Waiting for provider billing support (d) introduces significant delay when the information is already available in the access logs.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/ServerLogs.html","label":"AWS S3 Server Access Logging"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/access-logs","label":"Google Cloud Storage – Access Logs and Storage Logs"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security operations team notices that object storage buckets in their cloud environment are generating unusually high egress charges even though no new application features have been deployed. Access logs for the buckets are enabled. Which troubleshooting action will MOST efficiently identify the cause of the unexpected egress?$patch$);

-- CV0-004-P7: 41 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A solutions architect is designing a multi-tier web application on a public cloud platform. The application must remain available even if a single data center experiences a complete outage. Which architectural approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy all components within a single availability zone using auto-scaling groups"},{"id":"b","text":"Distribute application tiers across multiple availability zones within the same region"},{"id":"c","text":"Use a content delivery network (CDN) to cache static assets globally"},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the instance size of each tier to handle potential failover load"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Deploying across multiple availability zones (AZs) ensures that if one data center (AZ) fails, the other AZs continue serving traffic, satisfying the high-availability requirement. A single AZ deployment (option a) fails entirely when that AZ goes down. A CDN (option c) only addresses static content delivery, not full application availability. Vertical scaling (option d) does not address geographic redundancy and still represents a single point of failure.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/using-regions-availability-zones.html","label":"AWS: Regions and Availability Zones"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A solutions architect is designing a multi-tier web application on a public cloud platform. The application must remain available even if a single data center experiences a complete outage. Which architectural approach BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization needs a cloud deployment model that allows it to keep sensitive patient records on-premises while leveraging public cloud resources for less-sensitive workloads such as web frontends. Which deployment model BEST fits this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Public cloud"},{"id":"b","text":"Private cloud"},{"id":"c","text":"Hybrid cloud"},{"id":"d","text":"Community cloud"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A hybrid cloud model combines on-premises (private) infrastructure with public cloud resources, connected via secure networking. This allows the organization to keep regulated data on-premises while using the public cloud for less-sensitive workloads. A pure public cloud (option a) would not satisfy on-premises data residency needs. A pure private cloud (option b) foregoes public cloud elasticity. A community cloud (option d) is shared among organizations with similar compliance requirements but does not inherently provide on-premises control for one specific organization.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-145/final","label":"NIST SP 800-145: The NIST Definition of Cloud Computing"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization needs a cloud deployment model that allows it to keep sensitive patient records on-premises while leveraging public cloud resources for less-sensitive workloads such as web frontends. Which deployment model BEST fits this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is evaluating service models for a new internal analytics platform. The team wants maximum control over the operating system, middleware, and runtime environments, but does not want to manage physical hardware. Which cloud service model BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Software as a Service (SaaS)"},{"id":"b","text":"Platform as a Service (PaaS)"},{"id":"c","text":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)"},{"id":"d","text":"Function as a Service (FaaS)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$IaaS provides virtualized compute, storage, and networking, giving the team full control over the OS, middleware, and runtime while abstracting physical hardware management. SaaS (option a) offers no control over the underlying stack. PaaS (option b) abstracts the OS and middleware, limiting control. FaaS (option d) is even more abstracted, managing execution environments automatically and providing no OS-level control.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/sp/800-145/final","label":"NIST SP 800-145: The NIST Definition of Cloud Computing"},{"url":"https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/resources/cloud-computing-dictionary/what-is-iaas/","label":"Microsoft Azure: What is IaaS?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is evaluating service models for a new internal analytics platform. The team wants maximum control over the operating system, middleware, and runtime environments, but does not want to manage physical hardware. Which cloud service model BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a capacity planning session, a cloud architect is told that a workload experiences highly unpredictable traffic spikes throughout the day, followed by long periods of minimal activity. Which cloud design principle BEST addresses this scenario while minimizing cost?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Over-provision resources to ensure peak demand is always met"},{"id":"b","text":"Implement elasticity by automatically scaling resources in and out based on demand"},{"id":"c","text":"Use reserved instances sized for the peak load to lock in lower pricing"},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy the workload across multiple regions to distribute load evenly"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Elasticity allows resources to automatically scale out during traffic spikes and scale in during low-activity periods, directly matching resource consumption to demand and minimizing cost. Over-provisioning (option a) wastes money during idle periods. Reserved instances sized for peak (option c) also incurs unnecessary cost during low-traffic windows. Multi-region deployment (option d) improves geographic redundancy but does not inherently reduce cost for unpredictable spikes.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/wellarchitected/latest/performance-efficiency-pillar/welcome.html","label":"AWS Well-Architected Framework: Performance Efficiency Pillar"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a capacity planning session, a cloud architect is told that a workload experiences highly unpredictable traffic spikes throughout the day, followed by long periods of minimal activity. Which cloud design principle BEST addresses this scenario while minimizing cost?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect needs to design a disaster recovery solution with a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of less than 15 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of less than 5 minutes for a mission-critical database. Which DR strategy BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Backup and restore using daily snapshots stored in object storage"},{"id":"b","text":"Pilot light with core database services replicated to a secondary region"},{"id":"c","text":"Warm standby with a scaled-down but fully functional replica running in a secondary region"},{"id":"d","text":"Multi-site active/active deployment with synchronous replication across regions"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An active/active multi-site deployment with synchronous replication provides near-zero RPO (data loss is virtually eliminated) and near-zero RTO (traffic can be instantly redirected), easily meeting the <15-minute RTO and <5-minute RPO targets. Backup and restore (option a) can take hours to restore, violating both objectives. Pilot light (option b) requires manual intervention to scale and promote services, typically resulting in RTO of 30–60+ minutes. Warm standby (option c) can achieve moderate RTOs but may still require promotion time and does not guarantee sub-5-minute RPO without synchronous replication.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS Disaster Recovery Whitepaper"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect needs to design a disaster recovery solution with a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of less than 15 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of less than 5 minutes for a mission-critical database. Which DR strategy BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization is designing a cloud-native application and wants to ensure that individual application components can be developed, deployed, and scaled independently without impacting other components. Which architectural pattern BEST supports this goal?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Monolithic architecture deployed on a single virtual machine"},{"id":"b","text":"Three-tier architecture with shared middleware"},{"id":"c","text":"Microservices architecture with independently deployable services"},{"id":"d","text":"Service-oriented architecture (SOA) using a centralized enterprise service bus (ESB)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Microservices architecture decomposes an application into small, independently deployable services, each responsible for a specific business capability. This allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale each service independently. A monolith (option a) must be deployed as a whole unit. A three-tier architecture with shared middleware (option b) still creates coupling at the middleware layer. SOA with a centralized ESB (option d) introduces a central bottleneck and point of coupling that limits independent deployment.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/guide/architecture-styles/microservices","label":"Microsoft Azure: Microservices Architecture Style"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/architecture/microservices-architecture-introduction","label":"Google Cloud: Microservices Architecture on Google Cloud"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization is designing a cloud-native application and wants to ensure that individual application components can be developed, deployed, and scaled independently without impacting other components. Which architectural pattern BEST supports this goal?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect is selecting a storage tier for a dataset that is accessed frequently throughout the business day but must also be highly durable with no single points of failure. Which storage characteristic is MOST critical to evaluate when selecting the appropriate cloud storage service?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Archival retrieval latency"},{"id":"b","text":"Durability and throughput for frequent access patterns"},{"id":"c","text":"Cold storage pricing per gigabyte"},{"id":"d","text":"Maximum object retention lock period"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$For a dataset accessed frequently during business hours, the critical storage characteristics are high durability (ensuring data is not lost and has no single points of failure) and sufficient throughput/IOPS to support frequent access without latency issues. Archival retrieval latency (option a) is irrelevant for frequently accessed data. Cold storage pricing (option c) applies to infrequently accessed data tiers. Object retention lock periods (option d) relate to compliance and immutability features, not availability or performance.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/storage-best-practices-for-backup-and-restore/storage-best-practices-for-backup-and-restore.html","label":"AWS Storage Best Practices Whitepaper"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/storage-redundancy","label":"Microsoft Azure Storage Redundancy Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect is selecting a storage tier for a dataset that is accessed frequently throughout the business day but must also be highly durable with no single points of failure. Which storage characteristic is MOST critical to evaluate when selecting the appropriate cloud storage service?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise architect is designing a cloud solution that must comply with a regulatory requirement mandating that all data processing and storage occur within a specific geographic country. Which cloud design consideration PRIMARILY addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Implementing data encryption at rest using customer-managed keys"},{"id":"b","text":"Enforcing data residency by restricting resource deployment to cloud regions within the required country"},{"id":"c","text":"Using a private cloud model to prevent any data from leaving the corporate data center"},{"id":"d","text":"Enabling geo-redundant replication to automatically mirror data to the nearest available region"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Data residency requirements mandate that data is stored and processed within a specific geographic boundary. The correct approach is to restrict cloud resource deployment exclusively to regions located within the required country, using cloud provider region-locking policies or governance controls. Encryption at rest (option a) protects data confidentiality but does not control where data resides. A private cloud (option c) could work but is not the primary cloud design consideration—many organizations use public cloud regions to meet residency requirements. Geo-redundant replication (option d) actively moves data across regions, potentially violating residency requirements.$patch$, $patch$Cloud Architecture and Design$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/explore/global-infrastructure/data-residency/","label":"Microsoft Azure: Data Residency in Azure"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/data-residency/data-residency.html","label":"AWS: Data Residency – AWS Policy Perspectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An enterprise architect is designing a cloud solution that must comply with a regulatory requirement mandating that all data processing and storage occur within a specific geographic country. Which cloud design consideration PRIMARILY addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a new application that requires zero downtime during future updates. The deployment strategy must route a small percentage of live traffic to the new version before a full rollout. Which deployment strategy BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Recreate deployment"},{"id":"b","text":"Canary deployment"},{"id":"c","text":"Blue/Green deployment"},{"id":"d","text":"Rolling deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A canary deployment gradually shifts a small percentage of live traffic to the new version, allowing engineers to validate behavior before a full rollout. Recreate deployment takes the old version down before the new version goes up, causing downtime. Blue/Green swaps all traffic at once between two identical environments—useful for zero downtime but does not incrementally route a small percentage. Rolling deployment updates instances incrementally but does not natively support percentage-based traffic splitting to the new version the way canary does.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/architecture/application-deployment-and-testing-strategies","label":"Google Cloud - Deployment Strategies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is deploying a new application that requires zero downtime during future updates. The deployment strategy must route a small percentage of live traffic to the new version before a full rollout. Which deployment strategy BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization is migrating a monolithic application to containers. They need to define the CPU and memory limits for each containerized service. Which configuration file format is MOST commonly used in Kubernetes to declare these resource constraints?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"JSON manifest with apiVersion and kind fields"},{"id":"b","text":"YAML manifest with resources.requests and resources.limits fields"},{"id":"c","text":"TOML configuration with [resources] table"},{"id":"d","text":"INI file with [cpu] and [memory] sections"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Kubernetes uses YAML (or JSON) manifests to define Pod and container specifications. Resource constraints are declared under the spec.containers[].resources field with sub-fields requests (guaranteed minimum) and limits (maximum allowed). While Kubernetes does accept JSON, YAML is the idiomatic and most widely used format. TOML and INI are not supported Kubernetes manifest formats.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/","label":"Kubernetes - Resource Management for Pods and Containers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization is migrating a monolithic application to containers. They need to define the CPU and memory limits for each containerized service. Which configuration file format is MOST commonly used in Kubernetes to declare these resource constraints?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants to deploy infrastructure using code so that environments are reproducible and version-controlled. Which of the following tools is specifically designed for Infrastructure as Code (IaC) and is cloud-agnostic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS CloudFormation"},{"id":"b","text":"Azure Bicep"},{"id":"c","text":"HashiCorp Terraform"},{"id":"d","text":"Google Deployment Manager"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$HashiCorp Terraform is a cloud-agnostic IaC tool that uses HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language) and supports multiple providers including AWS, Azure, GCP, and many others. AWS CloudFormation is specific to AWS, Azure Bicep is specific to Azure, and Google Deployment Manager is specific to GCP. Terraform's provider model makes it the standard choice when multi-cloud or cloud-agnostic IaC is required.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/docs","label":"HashiCorp Terraform Documentation"},{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants to deploy infrastructure using code so that environments are reproducible and version-controlled. Which of the following tools is specifically designed for Infrastructure as Code (IaC) and is cloud-agnostic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud deployment, a team needs to ensure that configuration data such as database connection strings are not stored in the application code or container images. Which approach BEST satisfies this security requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Hard-code the connection strings in the Dockerfile ENV instruction"},{"id":"b","text":"Store connection strings in environment variables injected at runtime via a secrets manager"},{"id":"c","text":"Embed connection strings in a base64-encoded layer of the container image"},{"id":"d","text":"Place connection strings in a public Git repository under the config folder"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Injecting secrets at runtime via a dedicated secrets manager (such as AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, or HashiCorp Vault) keeps sensitive data out of source code and container images. Hard-coding in Dockerfiles or embedding in image layers exposes secrets to anyone who can pull the image. Storing credentials in a public Git repository is a critical security violation. The runtime-injection approach is the industry standard for the 12-factor app methodology.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/intro.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager Documentation"},{"url":"https://12factor.net/config","label":"12-Factor App - Config"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud deployment, a team needs to ensure that configuration data such as database connection strings are not stored in the application code or container images. Which approach BEST satisfies this security requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is asked to deploy a stateful database workload in Kubernetes that requires stable network identities and persistent storage even after pod restarts. Which Kubernetes object should they use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deployment"},{"id":"b","text":"DaemonSet"},{"id":"c","text":"StatefulSet"},{"id":"d","text":"ReplicaSet"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$StatefulSet is designed for stateful applications that require stable, unique network identifiers, stable persistent storage, and ordered deployment/scaling. Deployments and ReplicaSets are designed for stateless workloads and do not guarantee pod identity or ordered operations. DaemonSets ensure one pod per node, which is used for node-level services like log collectors, not stateful databases.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/statefulset/","label":"Kubernetes - StatefulSets"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is asked to deploy a stateful database workload in Kubernetes that requires stable network identities and persistent storage even after pod restarts. Which Kubernetes object should they use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization deploys two identical production environments (Blue and Green). The current live environment is Blue. After successfully testing an update on Green, the team needs to switch all user traffic to Green instantly. Which mechanism is MOST appropriate for redirecting traffic with minimal configuration changes?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Update the application's SSL certificate to point to the Green environment"},{"id":"b","text":"Update the DNS record to point to the Green environment's load balancer"},{"id":"c","text":"Terminate all Blue environment instances to force client reconnection"},{"id":"d","text":"Modify the application's database connection string to reference Green"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In a Blue/Green deployment, the standard traffic-switching mechanism is updating the DNS record (or updating the load balancer target group) to point to the new environment. This is fast, reversible, and requires no application changes. Terminating Blue instances forces reconnections but does not route traffic to Green cleanly. SSL certificate and database connection string changes are unrelated to traffic routing.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/overview-deployment-options/bluegreen-deployments.html","label":"AWS Blue/Green Deployments"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization deploys two identical production environments (Blue and Green). The current live environment is Blue. After successfully testing an update on Green, the team needs to switch all user traffic to Green instantly. Which mechanism is MOST appropriate for redirecting traffic with minimal configuration changes?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team wants to automate the building, testing, and deployment of code changes every time a developer pushes to the main branch. Which practice does this workflow describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment (CI/CD)"},{"id":"b","text":"Configuration Management"},{"id":"c","text":"Change Management"},{"id":"d","text":"Capacity Planning"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$CI/CD automates the pipeline from code commit through build, test, and deployment. Continuous Integration (CI) automatically builds and tests code on each commit; Continuous Deployment (CD) automatically deploys passing builds to production. Configuration Management deals with maintaining system state consistency. Change Management is a governance process for approving modifications. Capacity Planning addresses resource sizing.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://about.gitlab.com/topics/ci-cd/","label":"GitLab - What is CI/CD?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team wants to automate the building, testing, and deployment of code changes every time a developer pushes to the main branch. Which practice does this workflow describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud architect must deploy an application across multiple geographic regions to comply with data residency laws and minimize latency for global users. Which cloud concept directly addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Auto-scaling groups within a single Availability Zone"},{"id":"b","text":"Multi-region deployment with geo-based routing"},{"id":"c","text":"Single-region high-availability cluster"},{"id":"d","text":"Spot instance pools in a single region"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Multi-region deployment with geo-based routing places application resources in different geographic regions and routes users to the nearest region, satisfying both data residency requirements and latency goals. Single-region deployments—even across multiple Availability Zones—cannot fulfill data residency laws that require data to remain within a specific country or jurisdiction. Spot instance pools address cost optimization, not geographic distribution.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/implementations/multi-region-application-architecture/","label":"AWS - Multi-Region Architecture"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/architecture/patterns/geodes","label":"Azure - Geode pattern"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud architect must deploy an application across multiple geographic regions to comply with data residency laws and minimize latency for global users. Which cloud concept directly addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A team is deploying microservices and needs a way to manage service discovery, load balancing, observability, and traffic encryption between services without modifying application code. Which deployment component satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"API Gateway"},{"id":"b","text":"Service Mesh"},{"id":"c","text":"Content Delivery Network (CDN)"},{"id":"d","text":"Network Load Balancer"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A service mesh (e.g., Istio, Linkerd) uses sidecar proxies to handle service discovery, mutual TLS encryption, load balancing, and observability at the infrastructure layer without requiring application code changes. An API Gateway manages north-south (external) traffic, not east-west service-to-service communication. A CDN caches static content at edge locations. A Network Load Balancer handles TCP/UDP traffic but does not provide service mesh capabilities like mTLS or observability.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://istio.io/latest/docs/concepts/what-is-istio/","label":"Istio Service Mesh Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/app-mesh/latest/userguide/what-is-app-mesh.html","label":"AWS App Mesh Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A team is deploying microservices and needs a way to manage service discovery, load balancing, observability, and traffic encryption between services without modifying application code. Which deployment component satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is using Ansible to deploy a web application stack. The playbook must execute tasks in a specific sequence on multiple hosts. Which Ansible construct is used to group an ordered list of tasks applied to a set of hosts?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Role"},{"id":"b","text":"Handler"},{"id":"c","text":"Play"},{"id":"d","text":"Inventory"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In Ansible, a Play is the unit within a playbook that maps a set of hosts (from the inventory) to an ordered list of tasks. Roles are reusable bundles of tasks, variables, and files but must be called from within a play. Handlers are special tasks triggered by notifications from other tasks. The Inventory is the list of hosts and groups, not a task-execution construct.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.ansible.com/ansible/latest/playbook_guide/playbooks_intro.html","label":"Ansible Documentation - Working with Playbooks"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is using Ansible to deploy a web application stack. The playbook must execute tasks in a specific sequence on multiple hosts. Which Ansible construct is used to group an ordered list of tasks applied to a set of hosts?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is migrating virtual machines from an on-premises data center to the cloud. The project manager asks about the approach where the VMs are moved as-is to cloud-hosted virtual machines without re-architecting the application. Which migration strategy does this describe?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Refactoring (Re-architect)"},{"id":"b","text":"Replatforming (Lift and Reshape)"},{"id":"c","text":"Rehosting (Lift and Shift)"},{"id":"d","text":"Repurchasing (Drop and Shop)"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Rehosting, commonly called 'Lift and Shift,' moves workloads to the cloud with no changes to the application architecture. Replatforming makes minor optimizations (e.g., moving to a managed database) without changing core architecture. Refactoring involves re-architecting the application to be cloud-native. Repurchasing replaces the existing application with a SaaS product.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/enterprise-strategy/new-possibilities-seven-migration-strategies-for-moving-to-the-cloud/","label":"AWS - 7 Rs of Cloud Migration"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is migrating virtual machines from an on-premises data center to the cloud. The project manager asks about the approach where the VMs are moved as-is to cloud-hosted virtual machines without re-architecting the application. Which migration strategy does this describe?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy a Docker containerized application on a managed service that automatically handles the underlying compute infrastructure, including OS patching and scaling, without requiring the team to manage servers. Which service model BEST fits this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"IaaS virtual machine with Docker installed manually"},{"id":"b","text":"Serverless container service (e.g., AWS Fargate, Azure Container Apps)"},{"id":"c","text":"Bare-metal colocation with a container runtime"},{"id":"d","text":"On-premises Kubernetes cluster managed by the team"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Serverless container services like AWS Fargate or Azure Container Apps run containers without requiring teams to provision or manage the underlying servers. The cloud provider handles OS patching, scaling, and infrastructure management. IaaS VMs require manual OS management. Bare-metal colocation and on-premises Kubernetes clusters require significant hands-on infrastructure management, which contradicts the requirement.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/AWS_Fargate.html","label":"AWS Fargate Documentation"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/container-apps/overview","label":"Azure Container Apps Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy a Docker containerized application on a managed service that automatically handles the underlying compute infrastructure, including OS patching and scaling, without requiring the team to manage servers. Which service model BEST fits this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineer is writing a CI/CD pipeline and needs to ensure that application unit tests, integration tests, and security scans are executed BEFORE the artifact is deployed to production. Which pipeline concept ensures these checks gate the deployment?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Post-deployment hooks"},{"id":"b","text":"Quality gates"},{"id":"c","text":"Rollback triggers"},{"id":"d","text":"Feature flags"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Quality gates are conditions in a CI/CD pipeline that must pass before the pipeline can proceed to the next stage (e.g., deployment). They enforce standards like passing test suites and security scans. Post-deployment hooks run after deployment and cannot prevent a bad artifact from reaching production. Rollback triggers revert a deployed version after a failure is detected. Feature flags control feature visibility at runtime but do not gate pipeline stages.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.sonarsource.com/sonarqube/latest/user-guide/quality-gates/","label":"SonarQube - Quality Gates"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/devops/pipelines/release/approvals/gates","label":"Azure DevOps - Release Gates"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineer is writing a CI/CD pipeline and needs to ensure that application unit tests, integration tests, and security scans are executed BEFORE the artifact is deployed to production. Which pipeline concept ensures these checks gate the deployment?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud team is deploying an application using a rolling update strategy on a Kubernetes cluster. During the rollout, they want to ensure that at least 75% of the desired pods are available at all times. Which Kubernetes Deployment field controls this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxSurge"},{"id":"b","text":"spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.maxUnavailable"},{"id":"c","text":"spec.replicas"},{"id":"d","text":"spec.minReadySeconds"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The maxUnavailable field in a Kubernetes rolling update strategy defines the maximum number (or percentage) of pods that can be unavailable during the update. Setting maxUnavailable to 25% ensures at least 75% of pods remain available at all times. maxSurge controls how many extra pods above the desired count can be created. spec.replicas sets the total desired pod count. minReadySeconds specifies how long a pod must be ready before being considered available, but does not directly control the minimum availability percentage during a rollout.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/#rolling-update-deployment","label":"Kubernetes - Deployments Rolling Update Strategy"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud team is deploying an application using a rolling update strategy on a Kubernetes cluster. During the rollout, they want to ensure that at least 75% of the desired pods are available at all times. Which Kubernetes Deployment field controls this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy an application that must automatically scale out when CPU utilization exceeds 70% and scale in when it drops below 30%. Which cloud feature should be configured to achieve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Manual scaling with a scheduled task"},{"id":"b","text":"Vertical scaling (scaling up)"},{"id":"c","text":"Dynamic auto-scaling with target tracking or step scaling policy"},{"id":"d","text":"Reserved instance purchasing"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Dynamic auto-scaling policies (target tracking or step scaling) automatically add or remove compute instances based on real-time metric thresholds like CPU utilization. Target tracking policies attempt to keep a metric at a target value, while step scaling policies define scale-out and scale-in thresholds. Manual scaling with scheduled tasks requires prediction rather than reacting to actual load. Vertical scaling increases the size of individual instances rather than adding more. Reserved instances are a pricing model and do not provide automatic scaling.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-scale-based-on-demand.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling - Dynamic Scaling"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/autoscale/autoscale-overview","label":"Azure Monitor Autoscale"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer needs to deploy an application that must automatically scale out when CPU utilization exceeds 70% and scale in when it drops below 30%. Which cloud feature should be configured to achieve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A team is using a cloud provider's managed Kubernetes service to deploy an application. They need the Kubernetes cluster to automatically provision and attach a persistent block storage volume when a Pod requests it, without manual administrator intervention. Which Kubernetes object enables this dynamic provisioning?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"PersistentVolume (PV)"},{"id":"b","text":"PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) bound to a StorageClass"},{"id":"c","text":"ConfigMap"},{"id":"d","text":"EmptyDir volume"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) referencing a StorageClass triggers dynamic provisioning: when a Pod requests storage via PVC, the cloud provider's StorageClass provisioner automatically creates and attaches a PersistentVolume (e.g., an EBS volume on AWS or a Managed Disk on Azure). A PV defined manually requires administrator pre-provisioning. ConfigMaps store configuration data, not block storage. EmptyDir volumes are ephemeral and tied to the pod's lifecycle, not persistent.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/dynamic-provisioning/","label":"Kubernetes - Dynamic Volume Provisioning"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A team is using a cloud provider's managed Kubernetes service to deploy an application. They need the Kubernetes cluster to automatically provision and attach a persistent block storage volume when a Pod requests it, without manual administrator intervention. Which Kubernetes object enables this dynamic provisioning?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a cloud application deployment, the team discovers that the new version has a critical bug in production. They need to immediately revert all users back to the last known good version. Which deployment capability allows the team to quickly restore the previous stable state?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Rollback to a previous deployment revision"},{"id":"b","text":"Increasing the number of replicas of the current broken version"},{"id":"c","text":"Enabling read replicas on the database"},{"id":"d","text":"Applying a new SSL certificate to the load balancer"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Rolling back to a previous deployment revision restores the last known good version of the application rapidly, minimizing user impact. Most CI/CD tools and orchestration platforms (e.g., Kubernetes, AWS CodeDeploy) maintain deployment history and support one-command rollback. Increasing replicas of the broken version only amplifies the problem. Enabling read replicas affects database scalability, not application version. Applying an SSL certificate is unrelated to deployment version control.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/#rolling-back-a-deployment","label":"Kubernetes - Rolling Back a Deployment"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployments-rollback-and-redeploy.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy - Roll Back a Deployment"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a cloud application deployment, the team discovers that the new version has a critical bug in production. They need to immediately revert all users back to the last known good version. Which deployment capability allows the team to quickly restore the previous stable state?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations engineer is tasked with ensuring that a production workload automatically scales out during peak hours and scales in during off-peak hours without manual intervention. Which cloud capability BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Manual horizontal scaling triggered by support tickets"},{"id":"b","text":"Auto-scaling policies based on scheduled actions and metric-based thresholds"},{"id":"c","text":"Vertical scaling by upgrading the instance type once a month"},{"id":"d","text":"Deploying additional instances only when the SLA breach alert is triggered"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Auto-scaling policies that combine schedule-based actions (for predictable peak hours) with metric-based thresholds (for dynamic demand) allow workloads to scale out and in automatically without manual intervention. Manual scaling (a) defeats the automation requirement. Vertical scaling (c) requires downtime and is not automated in the same sense. Waiting for an SLA breach (d) is reactive and may already be too late to prevent user impact.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/auto-scaling-benefits.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling – Scheduled and Dynamic Scaling"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations engineer is tasked with ensuring that a production workload automatically scales out during peak hours and scales in during off-peak hours without manual intervention. Which cloud capability BEST satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$During a post-incident review, the team discovers that a critical virtual machine was terminated because an automated lifecycle policy misidentified it as an unused resource. Which operational control would BEST prevent this from recurring?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Disable all lifecycle management policies across the environment"},{"id":"b","text":"Apply resource tagging standards and configure exclusion rules in lifecycle policies based on tags"},{"id":"c","text":"Manually review all instances weekly and remove the automated policy"},{"id":"d","text":"Migrate all critical VMs to a separate cloud provider to avoid lifecycle policies"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Resource tagging with consistent naming conventions (e.g., Environment=Production, CriticalWorkload=true) enables lifecycle policies to include exclusion rules that protect critical resources from automated termination. Disabling all policies (a) removes cost governance. Manual weekly reviews (c) are error-prone and not scalable. Migrating to another provider (d) does not address the root cause and introduces unnecessary complexity.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/tag-editor/latest/userguide/tagging.html","label":"AWS Tagging Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$During a post-incident review, the team discovers that a critical virtual machine was terminated because an automated lifecycle policy misidentified it as an unused resource. Which operational control would BEST prevent this from recurring?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator needs to ensure that all changes made to infrastructure in a production environment are traceable, reversible, and peer-reviewed before deployment. Which practice BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Granting all administrators full access to directly modify production resources via the console"},{"id":"b","text":"Implementing Infrastructure as Code (IaC) stored in a version-controlled repository with a mandatory pull-request approval workflow"},{"id":"c","text":"Documenting all changes in a spreadsheet after they are applied"},{"id":"d","text":"Using snapshots of the environment taken once a week for rollback purposes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Infrastructure as Code (IaC) stored in a version-controlled repository (e.g., Git) with a pull-request approval workflow ensures all changes are auditable, peer-reviewed before being applied, and reversible by reverting commits. Direct console access (a) bypasses review and auditability. Post-hoc spreadsheet documentation (c) is not a preventive control. Weekly snapshots (d) provide limited rollback granularity and do not enforce peer review.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/devops/deliver/what-is-infrastructure-as-code","label":"Microsoft Learn – Infrastructure as Code"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator needs to ensure that all changes made to infrastructure in a production environment are traceable, reversible, and peer-reviewed before deployment. Which practice BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization's cloud monitoring system generates hundreds of low-priority alerts per day, causing the operations team to miss critical alerts. Which approach BEST addresses this problem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Disable all alerting and rely solely on end-user reports"},{"id":"b","text":"Tune alert thresholds, implement alert severity classification, and configure escalation policies to route critical alerts to on-call staff"},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the monitoring polling interval to reduce the number of alerts generated"},{"id":"d","text":"Assign one team member to read every alert regardless of severity"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Alert tuning (adjusting thresholds to reduce false positives), severity classification (categorizing alerts by impact), and escalation policies (routing critical alerts to on-call personnel) together reduce alert fatigue while ensuring critical events receive immediate attention. Disabling alerting (a) eliminates visibility. Increasing polling intervals (c) may cause delayed detection of real incidents. Assigning one person to all alerts (d) is not scalable and does not solve the signal-to-noise problem.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://cloud.google.com/monitoring/alerts/best-practices","label":"Google Cloud – Best Practices for Monitoring and Alerting"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization's cloud monitoring system generates hundreds of low-priority alerts per day, causing the operations team to miss critical alerts. Which approach BEST addresses this problem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is designing a backup strategy for a database that requires a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 1 hour and a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 30 minutes. Which backup approach BEST satisfies both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Full backups taken once every 24 hours stored in the same region"},{"id":"b","text":"Continuous transaction log backups every 15 minutes combined with automated failover to a warm standby replica"},{"id":"c","text":"Weekly full backups with manual restoration procedures documented in a runbook"},{"id":"d","text":"Snapshots taken every 2 hours with restoration requiring manual intervention averaging 2 hours"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Transaction log backups every 15 minutes ensure data loss is limited to at most 15 minutes, satisfying the 1-hour RPO. A warm standby replica with automated failover enables recovery within minutes, satisfying the 30-minute RTO. Daily full backups (a) have up to 24-hour data loss, violating the RPO. Weekly backups (c) violate both RPO and RTO. 2-hour snapshots (d) violate the RPO, and 2-hour manual recovery violates the RTO.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS – RPO and RTO in Disaster Recovery"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is designing a backup strategy for a database that requires a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of 1 hour and a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of 30 minutes. Which backup approach BEST satisfies both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team uses a ticketing system to manage cloud support requests. A recurring issue is that tickets are closed before the underlying problem is fully resolved, causing repeat incidents. Which ITIL-aligned process improvement would BEST address this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enforce a mandatory post-resolution validation step and require confirmation from the requester before ticket closure"},{"id":"b","text":"Automatically close all tickets after 48 hours regardless of status"},{"id":"c","text":"Assign all tickets to a single senior engineer to improve accountability"},{"id":"d","text":"Remove the ticketing system and handle all requests verbally"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Requiring a post-resolution validation step and explicit requester confirmation before closure aligns with ITIL Incident Management best practices, ensuring issues are fully resolved before the ticket lifecycle ends. This reduces repeat incidents caused by premature closure. Auto-closing tickets after 48 hours (b) exacerbates the problem. Assigning all tickets to one engineer (c) creates a bottleneck and does not address the closure process. Removing the ticketing system (d) eliminates auditability and tracking.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.axelos.com/certifications/itil-service-management/what-is-itil","label":"Axelos – ITIL Incident Management"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team uses a ticketing system to manage cloud support requests. A recurring issue is that tickets are closed before the underlying problem is fully resolved, causing repeat incidents. Which ITIL-aligned process improvement would BEST address this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants to reduce cloud spending without impacting workload performance. After analyzing utilization metrics, the engineer finds that most virtual machines are consistently running at less than 20% CPU utilization. Which optimization action should the engineer recommend FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediately terminate all underutilized virtual machines"},{"id":"b","text":"Right-size the virtual machines by migrating to smaller instance types that match the observed utilization pattern"},{"id":"c","text":"Purchase additional reserved instances to lock in lower pricing for all existing VMs"},{"id":"d","text":"Migrate all workloads to on-premises infrastructure to eliminate cloud costs"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Right-sizing—selecting instance types whose CPU, memory, and network resources align with actual utilization—is the first and most direct optimization step when underutilization is identified. It reduces costs without service interruption. Immediately terminating VMs (a) risks disrupting active workloads. Purchasing more reserved instances (c) locks spend without addressing the root inefficiency. Migrating to on-premises (d) is a large architectural decision that does not address the immediate over-provisioning problem.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cost-management/latest/userguide/ce-rightsizing.html","label":"AWS Cost Optimization – Right Sizing"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants to reduce cloud spending without impacting workload performance. After analyzing utilization metrics, the engineer finds that most virtual machines are consistently running at less than 20% CPU utilization. Which optimization action should the engineer recommend FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud operations team needs to provide evidence that a SaaS provider is meeting the agreed-upon availability SLA of 99.9% monthly uptime. Which document or artifact BEST provides this evidence?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The original contract signed at the start of the service engagement"},{"id":"b","text":"Monthly service reports generated from the provider's monitoring dashboard showing uptime metrics and any SLA credits issued"},{"id":"c","text":"A network diagram of the provider's infrastructure"},{"id":"d","text":"An informal email from the account manager confirming the service was available"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Monthly service reports that include uptime metrics, downtime incidents, and any SLA credits issued are the standard artifact used to validate SLA compliance. These reports provide quantitative, time-bound evidence against the defined 99.9% threshold. The original contract (a) defines the SLA terms but does not demonstrate compliance. A network diagram (c) describes architecture, not availability performance. An informal email (d) is not an authoritative or auditable record.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://www.microsoft.com/licensing/docs/view/Service-Level-Agreements-SLA-for-Online-Services","label":"Microsoft Azure SLA Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud operations team needs to provide evidence that a SaaS provider is meeting the agreed-upon availability SLA of 99.9% monthly uptime. Which document or artifact BEST provides this evidence?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer is implementing a patch management process for cloud-hosted virtual machines. The organization requires zero production downtime during patching. Which strategy BEST meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply patches directly to all production VMs simultaneously during business hours"},{"id":"b","text":"Use a rolling update strategy where patches are applied to a subset of instances at a time behind a load balancer, keeping the remainder in service"},{"id":"c","text":"Schedule a quarterly maintenance window that requires full production downtime"},{"id":"d","text":"Only patch development environments and leave production VMs unpatched to avoid risk"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A rolling update strategy removes a subset of instances from the load balancer pool, patches them, validates them, and returns them to service before proceeding to the next subset. This maintains service availability throughout the patching cycle, meeting the zero-downtime requirement. Patching all production VMs simultaneously (a) causes a complete outage. Quarterly downtime windows (c) violate the zero-downtime requirement. Leaving production VMs unpatched (d) is a critical security risk.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-patch.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager – Rolling Updates"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer is implementing a patch management process for cloud-hosted virtual machines. The organization requires zero production downtime during patching. Which strategy BEST meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations engineer needs to ensure that cloud workload logs are retained for 13 months to satisfy a regulatory audit requirement. The logs are rarely accessed after 30 days. Which storage approach optimizes both compliance and cost?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store all 13 months of logs in the highest-performance SSD-backed block storage tier"},{"id":"b","text":"Store logs in a standard access tier for the first 30 days, then automatically transition them to a low-cost archival storage tier for the remaining 11 months"},{"id":"c","text":"Delete logs after 30 days once they are no longer actively needed"},{"id":"d","text":"Print and store physical copies of all logs for 13 months in a secure facility"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$A tiered storage lifecycle policy that transitions logs from a standard (frequently accessed) tier to an archival (infrequently accessed) tier after 30 days satisfies the 13-month retention requirement while minimizing storage costs, since archival tiers are significantly cheaper. Keeping all logs in high-performance storage (a) is unnecessarily expensive. Deleting after 30 days (c) violates the regulatory retention mandate. Physical printing (d) is impractical, costly, and not scalable.$patch$, $patch$Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lifecycle-mgmt.html","label":"AWS S3 Lifecycle Policies and Storage Classes"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations engineer needs to ensure that cloud workload logs are retained for 13 months to satisfy a regulatory audit requirement. The logs are rarely accessed after 30 days. Which storage approach optimizes both compliance and cost?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud security engineer is reviewing the access control configuration for a multi-tenant SaaS application hosted on a public cloud provider. The application currently uses a single IAM role shared across all tenant workloads. The engineer must implement a model that ensures each tenant's data and resources are logically isolated and that permissions are granted based on the minimum access required to perform a given function. Which combination of actions BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a dedicated IAM role per tenant with scoped permission policies following the principle of least privilege, and enforce resource tagging to logically separate tenant environments."},{"id":"b","text":"Assign all tenant workloads to a single administrative IAM role and rely on application-layer logic to enforce data separation between tenants."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable multi-factor authentication (MFA) on the shared IAM role and rotate the associated access keys every 90 days to reduce exposure."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a network access control list (NACL) to block cross-tenant traffic at the subnet level and allow the shared IAM role to remain in place for operational simplicity."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Option A is correct because creating a dedicated IAM role per tenant with least-privilege permission policies directly addresses both the isolation and minimum-access requirements. Least privilege ensures each role can only perform the specific actions needed for its function, reducing the blast radius of a credential compromise. Resource tagging further enforces logical separation for billing, auditing, and policy enforcement. — Option B is incorrect because delegating isolation entirely to the application layer while maintaining a shared over-privileged IAM role violates the principle of least privilege and creates a single point of failure for access control. — Option C is incorrect because MFA and key rotation improve authentication hygiene but do not resolve the fundamental problem of a shared role granting excessive, undifferentiated access across all tenants. — Option D is incorrect because NACLs operate at the network layer and address traffic flow, not identity-based access control; the underlying IAM misconfiguration remains unresolved.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/training/resources/exam-objectives/comptia-cloud-cv0-004-exam-objectives","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives — Security Domain"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html#grant-least-privilege","label":"AWS IAM Best Practices: Grant Least Privilege"},{"url":"https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/SpecialPublications/NIST.SP.800-207.pdf","label":"NIST SP 800-207 Zero Trust Architecture — Least Privilege Principle"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud security engineer is reviewing the access control configuration for a multi-tenant SaaS application hosted on a public cloud provider. The application currently uses a single IAM role shared across all tenant workloads. The engineer must implement a model that ensures each tenant's data and resources are logically isolated and that permissions are granted based on the minimum access required to perform a given function. Which combination of actions BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud administrator notices that a production web application hosted on a public cloud provider is intermittently returning HTTP 503 errors to end users. The virtual machines backing the application are running and show normal CPU and memory utilization. Which troubleshooting step should the administrator perform FIRST?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Reboot all virtual machines in the application tier simultaneously to clear transient faults."},{"id":"b","text":"Check the health status and listener configuration of the load balancer sitting in front of the application tier."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the vCPU count of every virtual machine by one size tier."},{"id":"d","text":"Re-deploy the application from the last known-good snapshot."},{"id":"e","text":"Open a support ticket with the cloud provider and wait for a root-cause analysis report."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$HTTP 503 (Service Unavailable) errors with healthy VM metrics strongly point to a problem in the traffic distribution layer rather than the compute layer. The load balancer health probes may be failing, listener rules may be misconfigured, or the target group may have no healthy registered instances — all of which would cause 503s even when individual VMs appear healthy. Rebooting VMs (option a) risks additional downtime and does not address the actual symptom. Scaling up vCPUs (option c) is irrelevant when utilization is normal. Re-deploying from snapshot (option d) is disruptive and skips diagnostic steps. Opening a support ticket immediately (option e) delays resolution of something an administrator can diagnose directly. Following a structured troubleshooting methodology — working from the component closest to the reported symptom — means inspecting the load balancer first.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://www.comptia.org/certifications/cloud","label":"CompTIA Cloud+ CV0-004 Exam Objectives"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-troubleshooting.html","label":"AWS Elastic Load Balancing Troubleshooting Guide"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud administrator notices that a production web application hosted on a public cloud provider is intermittently returning HTTP 503 errors to end users. The virtual machines backing the application are running and show normal CPU and memory utilization. Which troubleshooting step should the administrator perform FIRST?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After migrating a relational database workload to a cloud-managed database service, developers report that application query response times have increased from an average of 40 ms to over 900 ms. The database CPU and IOPS metrics are both below 30% utilization. What is the MOST likely cause of the degraded performance?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The managed database service tier does not support the SQL dialect used by the application."},{"id":"b","text":"Network latency between the application tier and the database endpoint is too high because they are in different regions or availability zones."},{"id":"c","text":"The database storage volume is nearly full, causing write amplification."},{"id":"d","text":"The database engine version selected during migration is older than the on-premises version."},{"id":"e","text":"The cloud provider is throttling the database connection because of an expired license."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$When CPU and IOPS are both low yet query latency is very high, the bottleneck is almost always network round-trip time (RTT) rather than compute or disk resources. Placing the application tier and database endpoint in different regions (or even separate availability zones with high inter-AZ latency) can add hundreds of milliseconds of RTT per query, compounding for applications that issue many sequential queries. Option a is incorrect because a dialect mismatch would cause errors, not slow queries. Option c (storage nearly full) would show elevated IOPS wait times and would appear in disk metrics. Option d (older engine version) could affect feature availability but not necessarily cause 900 ms latency spikes. Option e (license throttling) is not a standard cloud provider behavior — managed database services are licensed as part of the service fee.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-sql/database/troubleshoot-common-connectivity-issues","label":"Azure SQL Database Performance Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/CHAP_BestPractices.html","label":"AWS RDS Best Practices — Network Considerations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After migrating a relational database workload to a cloud-managed database service, developers report that application query response times have increased from an average of 40 ms to over 900 ms. The database CPU and IOPS metrics are both below 30% utilization. What is the MOST likely cause of the degraded performance?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A cloud engineer receives alerts that an auto-scaling group has been continuously launching and terminating instances in a rapid cycle — a behavior sometimes called 'scaling thrash.' The scale-out policy is triggered when average CPU exceeds 70% for 1 minute, and the scale-in policy removes an instance when average CPU drops below 30% for 1 minute. What change would BEST resolve the thrashing condition?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Disable the scale-in policy entirely so that instances are never automatically removed."},{"id":"b","text":"Increase the cooldown period or use step/target-tracking scaling to allow newly launched instances time to absorb load before the next scaling evaluation."},{"id":"c","text":"Reduce the scale-out CPU threshold from 70% to 50% so that instances are added sooner."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch the application to a serverless function to avoid managing auto-scaling policies."},{"id":"e","text":"Increase the minimum instance count in the auto-scaling group to the same value as the maximum instance count."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Scaling thrash occurs when newly launched instances have not yet initialized and started handling traffic before the next metric evaluation fires. The most direct fix is to extend the cooldown period (or use a target-tracking/step-scaling policy with warm-up time), which prevents the auto-scaler from evaluating the metric again until the new instances are fully contributing — smoothing out the CPU signal and stopping the launch-terminate cycle. Option a eliminates scale-in entirely, wasting cost and defeating the purpose of auto-scaling. Option c lowers the scale-out threshold, which would make scale-out trigger even more aggressively and worsen the thrash. Option d is an architectural change that may not be feasible and does not directly address the troubleshooting scenario. Option e effectively sets a fixed fleet size, removing elasticity.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-scaling-cooldowns.html","label":"AWS Auto Scaling Cooldowns"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/autoscale/autoscale-best-practices","label":"Azure Virtual Machine Scale Sets Autoscale Best Practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A cloud engineer receives alerts that an auto-scaling group has been continuously launching and terminating instances in a rapid cycle — a behavior sometimes called 'scaling thrash.' The scale-out policy is triggered when average CPU exceeds 70% for 1 minute, and the scale-in policy removes an instance when average CPU drops below 30% for 1 minute. What change would BEST resolve the thrashing condition?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team reports that outbound connections from a cloud-hosted application server to an external REST API are failing. The application logs show 'Connection timed out' errors. Inbound traffic to the application from the internet works correctly. The application server does NOT have a public IP address. Which configuration item is the MOST likely cause of the failed outbound connections?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The application's TLS certificate has expired, blocking outbound HTTPS requests."},{"id":"c","text":"The virtual network's DNS resolver is returning incorrect IP addresses for external hostnames."},{"id":"b","text":"A NAT gateway is missing, misconfigured, or not associated with the subnet's route table, preventing instances without public IPs from reaching the internet."},{"id":"d","text":"The security group or network ACL on the application server is blocking inbound return traffic on ephemeral ports."},{"id":"e","text":"The cloud provider's backbone network is experiencing an outage on the peering link to the external API provider."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$An instance without a public IP address must use a NAT gateway (or equivalent egress device) to initiate connections to the internet. If the NAT gateway does not exist, is stopped, or the subnet's route table has no route directing 0.0.0.0/0 traffic to the NAT gateway, all outbound internet connections from private instances will time out — exactly matching the reported symptom. Inbound traffic still works because it is initiated from the internet and routed through a public-facing load balancer or bastion, which are separate resources. A TLS certificate expiry (option a) would produce a TLS handshake error, not a connection timeout. DNS issues (option c) would produce name-resolution errors in logs, not timeouts. Security group / NACL blocking return traffic (option d) is possible but less likely than a missing NAT gateway given the complete failure pattern. An ISP/backbone outage (option e) cannot be confirmed or resolved by the administrator and is a last-resort assumption.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/nat-gateway-troubleshooting.html","label":"AWS NAT Gateway Troubleshooting"},{"url":"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/nat-gateway/nat-overview","label":"Azure NAT Gateway Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team reports that outbound connections from a cloud-hosted application server to an external REST API are failing. The application logs show 'Connection timed out' errors. Inbound traffic to the application from the internet works correctly. The application server does NOT have a public IP address. Which configuration item is the MOST likely cause of the failed outbound connections?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team deploys a containerized microservice to a managed Kubernetes cluster. The pods start successfully, but the service is unreachable from other pods within the same cluster namespace. The service object is created and shows a valid ClusterIP. Which troubleshooting action is MOST likely to identify the root cause?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Delete and recreate the container image from the registry to rule out image corruption."},{"id":"b","text":"Verify that the label selectors defined in the Service specification match the labels applied to the pods, and confirm that at least one endpoint is registered."},{"id":"c","text":"Increase the CPU and memory resource limits on the pods to prevent throttling."},{"id":"d","text":"Redeploy the workload to a different node pool to avoid node-level network issues."},{"id":"e","text":"Rotate the cluster's TLS certificates because inter-pod communication requires mutual TLS by default."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$In Kubernetes, a Service routes traffic to pods whose labels match the selector defined in the Service's spec. If the selector labels do not exactly match the pod labels — even a minor typo or missing label — the Service will have an empty endpoints list and no traffic will be forwarded, even though the ClusterIP is assigned and the Service object exists. Checking 'kubectl describe service <name>' and verifying that ENDPOINTS shows at least one IP:port is the fastest way to confirm this. Image corruption (option a) would prevent pods from starting, not cause service routing failures when pods are already running. CPU/memory limits (option c) affect pod scheduling and throttling, not inter-pod routing. Redeploying to a different node pool (option d) is disruptive and skips logical diagnostic steps. Mutual TLS (option e) is not enforced by default in Kubernetes unless a service mesh (e.g., Istio) is installed and configured to do so.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-application/debug-service/","label":"Kubernetes Debugging Services"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Service — Concepts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'CV0-004-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team deploys a containerized microservice to a managed Kubernetes cluster. The pods start successfully, but the service is unreachable from other pods within the same cluster namespace. The service object is created and shows a valid ClusterIP. Which troubleshooting action is MOST likely to identify the root cause?$patch$);

